voice_to_text: Nicholas Nick Godejohn, Gypsy Rose Blanchard's ex boyfriend who was convicted of murdering her mother Deedee Blanchard, is still in prison amid Gypsy's release. Gypsy and Nick met on a dating website for Christian singles in 2013 when Gypsy was 21 years old. They spoke for two years strictly online, developing a relationship in which they starting a new life together, including getting married and starting a family. They then met for the first time in person in 2015 when they went to see the movie Cinderella. Their second in person meeting was in June of that year when Nick Godejohn traveled from Wisconsin to Missouri to act out their plan of killing Gypsy's mother, Deedee. Godejohn would later say that he believed killing Deedee it was both imperative to ensuring he and Gypsy could spend their lives together. On June 9th, 2015, after Deedee fell asleep, go to John entered the house and while Gypsy hid in the bathroom, he stabbed Deedee Blanchard to death. The two of them skipped town together and stayed in hiding for the next four days until eventually police caught up to them. The couple were then arrested and charged with Deedee Blanchard's murder. 2016 Gypsy Rose pleaded guilty to second degree murder and got a sentence of 10 years in prison. Nick Godejohn, on the other hand, was charged with first degree murder. At his trial in 2018, there was no dispute whether Godejohn was the one to actually kill DD, but his attorneys argued That he had been manipulated by Gypsy with this argument. They attempted to get his charges reduced to second degree murder, but they were unsuccessful, and in November 2018, Nick Godejohn was convicted of first degree murder and sentenced to life in prison. His sentencing hearing in February 2019, go to John said quote, I was blindly in love. That was always very much the case. Goda John had no history of violence, and it's reported that after the murder, he was very upset. In fact, he later told ABC 2020, quote, I felt horrible about it when me and her were in the hotel room and Gipsy kept on telling me, stop crying, there's no reason to cry, he said. I did what I did because I loved her. I really wanted a life with her. Later in 2019, Nick go to John gave an interview from prison for an oxygen special. In that interview, he said that him and Gypsy were soulmates. He said, those five days when I was actually with her, physically with her, those five days were the most intense and magical and inspiring days I've ever had. He also said, somehow I just knew deep within my heart, some way me and her would end up being together in the end. He said that's why he committed the murder. He wanted to make sure her mom was not going to harm her anymore. Go to John is currently serving his life sentence at the Potosi Correctional Center in Mineral Point, Missouri. In August 2022, he was in court asking for his conviction to be set aside and for a new trial to happen on the grounds that he had ineffective counsel, but in March 2023, his motion to vacate, set aside or correct judgment and sentence was denied. He will be remaining in prison for the rest of his life.

People that have woken up in bed with a stranger. What's your story? Last year, I was pulling double shifts at City General Hospital, working myself into the ground after a brutal 18 hour shift in the ER. I was basically a zombie. My apartment was 40 minutes away in the opposite direction, so I always crashed at my buddy Jake's Place downtown. He gave me a spare key months ago and said, make yourself at home whenever. Stumbled up to his front door at 6 a m. Completely dead on my feet. The key was under the mat, like always. I walked in, kicked off my shoes by the door, and barely made it to the spare bedroom before collapsing face first onto the bed. I was out cold in seconds. Six hours later, I woke up to someone staring at me. Not Jake. A woman sitting on the edge of the bed, holding a cup of coffee, just watching me sleep. My heart nearly exploded out of my chest. Who the hell are you? I shot up in bed, still in my scrubs. She didn't scream or freak out. She just tilted her head and asked, do you know where you are right now? That's when I looked around the room. Different curtains, different furniture. Definitely not Jake's place. Walls were painted yellow instead of white. There were plants everywhere. Female clothes hanging on a chair. Oh, my god. I started panicking. I'm so sorry. I thought this Was my friend's house. The key was under the mat, and I just. Jake moved out three weeks ago, she said calmly. I'm Emma. I live here now. My brain couldn't process this. The key was there. The door was unlocked. I left it unlocked because my plumber was supposed to come fix the kitchen sink this morning. I guess you got here first. I felt like the biggest idiot on the planet. Here I was some random guy in scrubs who just broke into this woman's house and slept in her bed for six hours. She had every right to call the cops on me. I was at work when you came in, she continued. I got home about an hour ago and found you passed out. I wasn't sure if you were dead or just really tired, so I've been sitting here trying to figure out what to do. Why didn't you wake me up sooner? She shrugged. You looked exhausted and you're wearing a hospital badge, so I figured you weren't some random creep, just someone who made a mistake. I showed her my ID badge and explained the whole situation about Jake never telling me he moved. Actually started laughing. That sounds exactly like something Jake would do. He left half his stuff here when he moved out, including this weird exercise bike that I can't figure out how to get rid of. We ended up sitting in her kitchen drinking coffee and laughing about how Awkward the whole thing was. She told me she was a teacher at the elementary school down the street. I told her about working at the hospital and how Jake was the worst friend ever for not mentioning he moved. He probably forgot, she said. When I met him during the apartment handover, he seemed pretty scattered. Nice guy, but definitely not the most organized. Before I left, she gave me Jake's new address. Turns out he moved literally two blocks away but never bothered to tell anyone. The weird part is Emma and I kept texting after that. She would send me pictures of weird things Jake left behind, like collection of rubber ducks or a half finished puzzle of a cat. I would send her pictures of crazy stuff from the ER. We started hanging out on purpose instead of by accident. Coffee dates, movie nights, walks around the neighborhood. She was easy to talk to and didn't judge me for being a complete mess most of the time. Eight months later, I was her plus one to her cousin's wedding. The cousin turned out to be Jake's new roommate. When Jake saw us together, his jaw hit the floor. Wait, you two know each other? Emma grinned and said, yeah, he broke into my house and slept in my bed. It was very romantic. Jake looked confused until I explained the whole story. Then he felt terrible for not telling me he moved, but Emma just laughed. And said it worked out perfectly. If you had told him, we never would have met. Sometimes the best things happen by accident. Two years later, Emma and I got engaged. Jake was my best man, obviously. During his speech, he said he took full credit for our relationship because his forgetfulness brought us together. Emma's maid of honor was her sister, who roasted Jake for being the most unreliable wing man in history. The whole wedding party was cracking up.

My manager said, only do what's in your job title. So I did. I worked at support at this small software company. Nothing fancy, 40 employees, basic office setup, cheap coffee that tasted like burnt rubber. My boss, Amina, was this quiet Pakistani woman who spoke English, Urdu, and German fluently. He'd been there five years and never caused drama. Our sales team constantly dragged her into client calls last minute. German clients loved talking to her in their language. Clients would light up when she switched to French mid conversation. She'd explain technical stuff they couldn't understand, translate error messages. Basically save deals that were falling apart. Then Brad became VP of sales. First week on the job, he called Amina into his office. I was fixing his computer when he told her she wasn't allowed on client calls anymore. Your IT support, not sales. Stay in your lane. Amina just nodded and went back to her desk. No argument, no drama. Just started staying in her cube when sales needed help. Week 2, chaos started. This German banking client called about API integration issues. Their whole marketing campaign depended on our software working perfectly. Sales guy Jake tried explaining the technical limitations, but kept messing up the terminology. Client got frustrated and hung up. They launched their campaign anyway. Cost them 2 million euros when our API couldn't handle their traffic volume. Exactly what Amina would have warned them about if she'd been on the call. Jake tried Calling back, but the client wouldn't pick up. They were furious, threatening legal action. Week three, French client Marseille Finance called about data export problems. Sarah from sales got on the call, but she doesn't speak French and they barely spoke English. 20 minutes of confused back and forth before they hung up and sent an angry email saying they were switching to our competitor. Brad kept blaming outdated documentation and unclear product specs in team meetings. Meanwhile, I'm in a quietly fixed bugs, answered support tickets and said nothing about the calls. She wasn't allowed on anymore. Month two got worse. Korean client needed urgent help with their payment gateway integration. Sales had nobody who spoke Korean. They used Google Translate over email for three days while the client system stayed broken. By day four, the client hired a different company and demanded a full refund. That's when the CEO Michelle noticed something weird. In the quarterly report, client retention dropped 15%. Support satisfaction scores tanked. Three major accounts threatened to leave. Board meeting time. Brad came in with a presentation blaming everything on legacy system limitations and inadequate technical resources. Said we needed to hire more sales engineers and upgrade our servers. Michelle asked if anyone else had thoughts about the retention problem. Amina raised her hand, first time she'd spoken up in months. May I show you something? She pulled up her laptop and showed call logs, email threads, technical tickets. Pointed out exactly where language barriers Caused confusion. Showed examples of clients asking technical questions that sales couldn't answer. Explained how small miscommunications snowballed into contract cancellations. I used to help bridge these gaps, she said quietly, but I'm following my job description now. Room went dead silent. You could hear the air conditioning humming. Michelle stared at Brad. You told her to stop joining client calls? Brad tried backtracking. Well, we need clear role boundaries. She just showed us. We lost half a million in revenue because of your clear role boundaries. Two weeks later, Emma got promoted to international client success manager. Raise bigger office equity package. She started joining calls again, and client satisfaction jumped back up. Brad transferred to internal process optimization, basically managing spreadsheets in the basement with no client contact.

I inherited millions, but kept it secret from my gold digging girlfriend. When my grandpa died last year, I expected maybe a few thousand dollars and his old fishing gear. Instead, I got his entire estate, $3 million, plus his house and investments. A lawyer made me promise to keep it quiet until I turned 25, which was still eight months away. So I did. I was dating Michelle at the time. We met at a food bank where we both volunteered. She was this artsy girl who painted murals and always wore thrift store clothes. She'd roll her eyes whenever her roommate bought expensive makeup and say things like, money just makes people shallow, and I'd rather be poor and happy than rich and fake. I believed her. I mean, she knew I worked at a grocery store making 12 bucks an hour and still wanted to hang out with me. She'd pay for our date sometimes because she made more money teaching art classes to kids. She seemed perfect, but then little things started bothering me. Like how she'd always forget her wallet when we went out with my friends who had better jobs. Or how she'd hint about wanting expensive stuff, but frame it like she was joking. Wouldn't it be crazy to spend $300 on shoes? Like, who does that? She'd say while staring at designer boots online. One night we were watching this movie where a guy finds out his girlfriend only dates him for money. Michelle laughed and said, that's so gross. I could never be with someone just for their bank account. But then she paused and added, though I guess it would be nice to not worry about rent all the time. I decided to test her. I told her my cousin was getting married and needed a plus one. The wedding was at some fancy country club. Michelle got so excited about going somewhere classy that she bought a 200 dollar dress. She couldn't afford the wedding. She kept asking my cousin's husband what he did for work and making comments about their gorgeous house and expensive cars. She barely talked to me all night. She was too busy networking with the rich relatives. That's when I knew, but I wanted to be absolutely sure, so I proposed. Figured if she really loved me, she wouldn't care about money, right? She said yes, crying and everything. Then I told her I wanted a prenup. A what? She asked, still wiping her tears. Prenuptial agreement. You know, just to protect both of us if things don't work out. She laughed. Jordan, you work at a grocery store. What exactly are you protecting? I kept my face straight. I might inherit some money someday. Plus you always say money doesn't matter to you anyway. She agreed immediately, said it was totally smart, and showed I was responsible. I drew up a simple prenup that basically said if we divorced, each person keeps what they Brought into the marriage, nothing crazy. Two weeks later, I handed it to her to sign. She read it, and her whole face changed. Wait. This says I get nothing if we divorce? Only if you don't bring anything into the marriage, I said. He told me money doesn't matter to you, so this should be fine, right? She stared at the paper like it was written in another language. But what if we're married for, like, 20 years and then split up? I'd have nothing. You'd have whatever you earned during those 20 years, and your art and your happiness, since money doesn't matter to you. She got quiet, real quiet. Then she said she needed time to think about it. Days turned into weeks. Every time I brought up the prenup, she'd find an excuse. She had a headache, she was stressed about work, she needed to ask her sister about it. Then she started crying randomly. Said the prenup made her feel like I didn't trust her, that it was insulting and unromantic. He'd guilt trip me by saying things like, I thought you loved me, and this feels like you're planning our divorce before we're even married. But I didn't budge. I just kept saying, if money doesn't matter to you, then this shouldn't be a problem. Finally, after six weeks of stalling, she exploded. Scream that she couldn't marry someone who didn't trust her, and that the prenup was proof I never really loved her. She threw the ring at me and stormed out. I was actually relieved

Teachers, have you ever met a student you looked up to? Her name was Jasmine, and she wore silence like armor. She sat in the second row of my 10th grade English class. Second seat from the left, closest to the wall. That's where she stayed. Never spoke unless called on. Never raised her hand. She turned in every assignment early and perfect, but never attached a single note or question. If I handed back essays with praise, she'd take them wordlessly and tuck them into her folder without making eye contact. Most students fade in and out. Jasmine didn't fade. She disappeared. No photos in the yearbook, no friends at lunch, no small talk in the halls. Still, she was impossible to ignore. One day in November, I gave the class a personal narrative prompt. Write about the most important moment of your life so far. Most kids wrote about birthdays or trips or siblings. Jasmine turned in a single page titled Wednesday. It wasn't poetic. No metaphors. Just a timeline. 6:00am alarm. Didn't sleep. 6:00am. Heard him downstairs. Waited until he left before showering. 7:00am burn on my left hand from stove. Hit it under my sleeve. 8:00am. Late to school. Told the office I had a dentist appointment. That was it. There was no climax, no conclusion. Just a quiet report of a morning that felt too specific to be fiction. I didn't know what to do with it, so I marked it a plus and slipped A sticky note inside. I'm here if you ever want to talk. She didn't reply. But the next week, she started staying after class, pretending to pack, slowly asking questions that barely needed answers. By December, I Learned she had no cell phone. By January, I noticed she wore the same coat every day, even indoors. In February, I figured out she never brought lunch because she didn't eat at school at all. Then one afternoon, the fire alarm went off unexpectedly during sixth period. Everyone filed out fast, but I couldn't find Jasmine. Not outside, not in the stairwell, not with her classmates. Finally found her crouched in the janitor's closet on the third floor, hands over her ears, face pale. I'm not supposed to leave unless I know where he is, she whispered. I didn't press. I just sat with her. The next day, she was absent. And the day after that. On day three, I walked to the counselor's office and asked for help. They said she wasn't listed under any emergency contacts. No working phone number, no listed address. Just a name and a forged signature on enrollment papers. Took a week for social services to step in. It took one night for everything to fall apart. That same week, I got a letter in my mailbox at school. Handwritten, folded into quarters. No return name. Just a sticky note stuck to the front that said, from Mister Lane. I'm sorry I didn't say goodbye. Inside, Was a three page letter from Jasmine. She explained that her mother died when she was 12, that her stepfather had moved them five times since then. To avoid questions, he taught her how to lie to landlords and forge documents, that she wasn't allowed to speak to other kids, that school was the only place she felt safe, and that I was the first adult who had ever waited for her to finish talking. That spring, I kept her chair open. Her name stayed on the roster. I left it there long after she was gone. Two years later, I got a letter from a group home a few towns over. She passed her GED and was applying to colleges. Said she still hated writing, but finally understood why it mattered.

Might women dislike the most if they were to become men? 1. Women might dislike the lack of physical affection and emotional support men often experience from friends. 2. Magically, no one cares about your feelings. 3. The amount of effort it takes to not be perceived as creep or perv, or the lack of benefit of the doubt. One example happened just the other day at the train station. Sat by myself, no one else here yet. As I'm early and it's a quiet station, I'm watching crap on my phone with my prescription sunglasses on. Excuse me, what do you think you're doing? I look up and some woman has stood staring at me. Huh? What? I'm confused as I've been pulled out of my little world. Why are you staring? And were you taking photos? I want to see your phone. I look around and in front of me were three very young teens in thong bikini, squatting down, waiting for the train. And I realize what the woman must have been thinking. I'm autistic and struggle with public confrontation at the best of times. All my rights to privacy go out the window now. If I argue, she will call the police. If I walk away, I look guilty. As the station is filling up, more people are now staring at me and this woman shouting at me. I have to show her my recent photos, and she accuses me of using another app. The train Then pulls up and I tell her to piss off and she starts screaming pedo. I had to get off that train and wait for the next as she was following me shouting perv and pedo. I was lucky I didn't get my head kicked in thanks to her. Can you imagine what it feels like to have 50 odd people giving you disgusted and threatening looks thanks to a shit set of circumstance?

Spiked my drink at a party, so I made him terrified of liquids. You know that one guy at every party? The one who thinks he's God's gift to alcohol and women? The guy who says things like I mix better than I date, and if you can't handle a little fun, go home? Yeah, that guy. For me, that guy had a name. Mason. Mason was the kind of guy who wore sunglasses indoors and took shirtless mirror pics like it was a civic duty. He thought spiking people's drinks was hilarious. Just a little joke, bro. He's like slipping something into someone's drink was on par with drawing a mustache on a passed out friend. Spoiler alert it's not. I found out the hard way. It was during our friend Bailey's New Year's party. Good people, decent music, enough food to soak up the bad decisions. I grabbed a drink off the kitchen island. Non alcoholic cause I was the designated driver. Took a few sips. It tasted a little weird. Like if regret had a flavor. I figured maybe the soda was flat. Ten minutes later, the room started spinning like it was trying to detach from earth. I barely made it to the bathroom before my legs went full jello. My heart was racing, skin crawling, and I was suddenly having a deep, personal conversation with the floor tiles. Bailey found me an hour later, curled up like a shrimp in her tub. She called an ambulance. Thank god. Turns out Mason had decided to spice up the party by adding something to my drink. Something prescription based. Something not meant for conscious humans. He thought it was funny. Dude, you should have seen your face, he said, laughing when I confronted him. Relax, I gave you the light stuff. Ah, yes, just a sprinkle of involuntary coma. How festive. I wanted to punch him, but I'm not stupid. People forget bruises, but they don't forget fear. Especially the kind that seeps in drop by drop. So I made a decision. Mason was going to become terrified of liquids. All of them. The plan took finesse. I couldn't just scream revenge and run at him with a water balloon. This had to feel like karma was slowly dripping down his neck. And it started with coffee. I knew Mason's routine. Every morning, same cafe, same order. Iced triple espresso with oat milk, vanilla, two pumps of ego. So I applied for a job at that cafe. Not because I needed it, but because revenge requires commitment. After three weeks of being the overly eager new guy, I got barista duty. And when Mason walked in, I greeted him with my best you probably don't remember drugging me smile. He didn't recognize me. Perfect. I made his drink. Nothing in it yet, but after handing it to him, I leaned over and said, we've had a few complaints about mold in the oat milk. Let us

But there I was, sweating in my hoodie on the hottest day of summer, staring at the neon sign flickering above the door. I was a college student, getting bullied daily about my burn scars. Kids would whisper crispy when I walked by. I ate lunch alone, always in long sleeves, always hiding from their stairs. And cruel jokes. Deep, raised tissue that made people stare and whisper. I'd been to four shops already. Each one took one look and said they couldn't work with damaged skin like mine. His face didn't change, but I saw the quick intake of breath. The scars ran from my wrist to my elbows. Twisted, discolored skin that told the story of the worst night of my life. I. I understand if you can't. I started. Jake, the owner, called to a guy in the corner, come take a look at this. Jake was intimidating at first glance. Tall, broad shouldered, covered head. To toe in intricate tattoos, a neck piece of a Phoenix wrapped around his throat. He barely spoke to customers, just focused intensely on his work. For the next hour, Jake sketched ideas. He showed me concepts that incorporated my scars instead of hiding them. Flowing designs that followed every line of raised skin. Why do you understand this so well? I finally asked. Jake's hand froze mid sketch. He glanced around the shop, then back at me with an expression I couldn't read. Can you stay after closing tonight? He asked quietly. There's something I need to show you first. The rest of the day crawled by. Other customers came and went, but Jake kept stealing glances at me. 9 p m. My husband called me a weaponized fatty after I asked him to help me with the kids. So I gave him a taste of my weaponized silent treatment and now he is furious. I just had a baby a few months ago and I have a special needs toddler. My husband and I don't have any help from friends or family for our kids. I'm on my own all day with the kids and I'm exhausted all the time. And admittedly, I have not been the most pleasant person to be around since postpartum. I have suspected for a few months now that I might have postpartum depression. I have mood swings, sometimes I cry because I feel overwhelmed and helpless all the time. Or I act like a general butthole on purpose. I do my son's night feeds mostly on my own, and my husband will help whenever he can. A few days ago I told him I needed a nap slash break and that I wanted to take it with our baby as I got up twice that night for night feeds. Naps are a luxury that we get to have when the both of us are home. He had two breaks with our baby already that day. While I was looking after our special needs toddler, I asked him if he could help do a couple of chores. Nothing major, just to unload the dishwasher and to finish helping our toddler with their dinner when I came Out over an hour later. Nothing was done. Dishes not unloaded, toddler's plate basically full. House was in a mess. There were toys all over the floor. Husband was looking at his phone. I asked him what he had been doing this entire time. He said he was feeding our son. I don't know how entirely true this was, as our son's plate looked more or less the same as when I left. Normally, I would just do all the chores as usual, but this time I lost it. I felt like I was being punished for wanting a break. I lost my mind, and I yelled something about weaponizing incompetence and about how I am on my own all the time to do everything on my own, and how I only wanted a short break today, and I didn't understand why he couldn't help out and do more. I also mentioned how each of these chores took a few minutes to do, and I didn't understand why he couldn't finish them even though he had over an hour to do them. Then I took our baby to the room to get him changed, and my husband followed us and yelled something along the lines of, hey, fatty, why are you so fat? And then he came into the room with a family picture of us. I looked very unflattering in that picture. You can see how overweight I am in it. And held it up to my face and Said, weren't you supposed to lose weight like me? What is this weaponized fattiness? I stood there in shock, and I basically blanked out and didn't hear what else he said about my weight. But I heard the last part where he said I would end up like my mom with diabetes and in a wheelchair. And I heard him mention the words weaponized cuntiness. I went to the kitchen where he was, and he saw me and said something along the lines of how he should have taken a picture of my face when he insulted me. I got so angry and upset when he said that that I took the ugly picture that he held in my face off of the fridge door and tore it. Then I saw some other pictures of us, including our wedding pictures, and tore that, too. I was just so angry and upset. I should have controlled myself, but I didn't. Later on, I cried about what my husband said to me, and I took off my wedding ring, and I don't want to wear it. When I look at him, all I can think of is how he made fun of my weight, and I feel ashamed that this is what he has thought of me all along. I'm exhausted all the time, and on top of that, I'm pumping slash breastfeeding, and I'm hungry and thirsty all the time. Sometimes I don't get to eat until late at night. And I don't always make the best food choices. I do try and get out every day for walks with the kids as part of exercise, but I don't have any time to myself to do anything. All my time and energy is being given to my children all day, and it takes a lot out of me. I have not spoken to my husband since, and he's called me mean for giving him the silent treatment. I can't get past what he said. Just can't do it. I know. I'm a butthole, too.

I found out why my autistic daughter screams every Tuesday at three PM. The school janitor had been quietly saving her for months. I used to dread Tuesdays. Every week, like clockwork, my 12 year old daughter Lily would come home from school and have a complete meltdown at exactly three PM. Not the typical tantrums most parents navigate. Pair these for full body primal scream that would last for hours. Lily has nonverbal autism. She communicates through a tablet app, but emotional moments often leave her without words. When I'd ask what happened on Tuesdays, she just rock back and forth. Tablet abandoned. I tried everything. Changed her Tuesday lunch, requested different classes, even drove her to school myself instead of letting her take the special needs bus. Nothing worked. The school counselor suggested it might be sensory overload from Tuesday's gym class, but removing her from P didn't help. Last month I reached my breaking point after a particularly brutal meltdown where Lily scratched her arms until they bled. I decided to pick her up early the following Tuesday to observe what might be triggering her. At 2:30 p. M, I arrived at school and signed in at the office. Instead of announcing my arrival, I asked if I could quietly observe for a few minutes. Principal, knowing our struggles, agreed. I found Lily's class in the library. She wasn't having a meltdown, Pern. She was sitting calmly at a table, focused on a book about butterflies. My Confusion deepened as the class lined up to return to their room. I followed at a distance. That. That's when I noticed an older man in a gray janitor's uniform, watching the hallway intently. I can't give students a zero for using AI unless I have proof. As a high school teacher, it's becoming impossible to fight against technology. Sure, I can spot AI writing, the awkward phrasing, the weird vocabulary choices, and that oddly formal tone that no teenager would naturally use. But proving it? That's another story. Last month, I caught Dylan using chat GPT for his essay on The Great Gatsby. His writing suddenly jumped from barely coherent to graduate level analysis. I called him out. He got defensive. You can't just accuse me without evidence, he said. His mom called that afternoon, threatening to contact the principal. My department head sympathized, but warned me that without concrete proof, I couldn't give zeros. Their parents will fight it, and administration will cave, he said. I needed a foolproof method, so I designed a little experiment. For their next assignment, I created a seemingly normal essay prompt about personal experiences. But buried in the middle of the instructions was one specific line. Include the phrase purple elephants dance at midnight somewhere in your conclusion. I made sure to read the full instructions allowed in class, including that line. I even paused and repeat, don't forget about the purple elephants, I said. Several students giggled and wrote it down. Two days later, I collected 27 essays. 18 of them mentioned purple elephants in their conclusion. Nine didn't mention it at all. Those nine essays also happened to be slightly well written. With that Telltale AI formality. When Emma asked why she got a zero, I simply pointed to the instructions. But I didn't see that part, she stammered. Funny, I replied. AI doesn't read instructions either. The next day, my classroom was unusually quiet. Word had spread. The AI users knew they'd been caught. The best part? Two students actually confessed and asked to redo their assignments. Honestly, my little purple elephant's trick has become my secret weapon. Sometimes I use random phrases, sometimes weird formatting requirements. The students who actually read instructions pass easily. The ones who just prompt A I, they fail themselves. No more accusations, no more arguments. Just students learning that shortcuts have consequences. And maybe, just maybe, they'll actually start reading the instructions.

How did your parents fail you? My mom always insisted I take piano lessons. But when I finally made it to a major competition, she didn't even show up. For 10 years, she drove me to lessons twice a week. You have a gift, she'd say, hovering over me while I practiced. She critiqued every note, timing my sessions with her phone. I hated it at first, but eventually fell in love with playing. When I qualified for the state championship, mom went into overdrive. She scheduled extra practices, recorded me playing, and even bought me a new outfit. This could open doors for your future, she kept saying. The night before, she helped me rehearse until midnight on competition day, I sat backstage, fingers trembling. I kept checking my phone. Mom had texted she was running late, but would definitely make it. My turn came, and I walked onto the stage. I scanned the audience. No sign of her. My heart sank, but I played anyway. Somehow, it was my best performance ever. I won second place. Judge called it emotionally compelling. As other parents rushed to congratulate their kids, I stood alone with my trophy. I called mom five times, straight to voicemail. When I finally got home, I found her asleep on the couch. Wine glass tipped over on the carpet. Her phone showed she'd been texting her new boyfriend all afternoon. She woke up, saw my trophy, and had the nerve to say, see, I always Knew you had talent. I just walked to my room and closed the door. The next day, I told her I was done with piano lessons.

How did you trick your entire high school? Our school had this ancient intercom system that barely worked half the time. The thing was installed in like 1985 and would randomly screech with feedback or just cut out completely during morning announcements. Teachers would roll their eyes and keep teaching through the static. During detention cleanup one Friday, I'm stuck organizing old equipment in the basement when I spot this forgotten room behind a dusty door. Inside are the original intercom controls. This massive metal panel with analog switches and a microphone that looks like it belongs in a museum. I couldn't believe it, but the master keys to every room in the school were just sitting on a rusty hook next to the controls. My heart starts racing because I realize what this means. This is the backup system they forgot about when they installed the newer one upstairs. Why do the only valid thing I could at this point? I grab my Pookie Bear Marcus out of last. Now Marcus does these perfect voice impressions. This kid can sound like anyone. Teachers, celebrities, even our principal, Mister Henderson. We sneak into school at 6:00am Monday morning through the gym entrance that never locks properly. The hallways are completely empty except for a few janitors who don't even notice us. We slip into the basement room and Marcus practices Henderson's voice while I figure out which switches control the main speakers. Exactly 9:15, right when every teacher is taking Attendance and the school is at maximum capacity. Marcus leans into the old microphone. He clears his throat and perfectly nails the principal. Both tone. Attention students and faculty. Due to a suspected gas leak in the East Wing, we are implementing emergency dismissal procedures. All classes will be dismissed at 11:30 a m. Repeat, emergency dismissal at 11:30. Buses are being dispatched immediately. Even better, though, was that three days earlier, I'd already hacked into the school's email system using a password I saw a teacher type in. I sent a fake maintenance alert to every single teacher and staff member saying there might be an early dismissal this week for emergency infrastructure repairs and to watch for announcements. We could hear distant cheers echoing through the air vents as students in classrooms above us started celebrating. Teachers were probably confused, but figured it was legitimate since they'd gotten that email warning. At exactly 11:30, kids start packing up their backpacks. Teachers pull out their phones, see that maintenance email from Friday, and assume this is what it was referring to. Within 10 minutes, it's complete chaos. 1 400 students flooding every exit like a coordinated fire drill that nobody planned. Meanwhile, the real Principal Henderson is 30 miles away at some boring district meeting about standardized testing. By noon, our school looks like a zombie apocalypse movie set. Empty hallways, abandoned backpacks, classroom doors hanging open. The few teachers left are standing around looking completely lost, wondering if They missed some important memo about evacuation procedures. Security cameras caught absolutely nothing because we used the forgotten analog system that isn't even connected to their digital monitoring. The IT department spent three entire days investigating a gas leak that never existed, calling utility companies and checking air quality. They interviewed random students, reviewed email logs, even brought in some district security expert. Everyone just shrugged and said they heard the announcement and followed emergency procedures like they were supposed to. Marcus and I kept completely quiet. Even when our friends were talking about the mysterious early dismissal at lunch the next week. We just nodded along and acted as confused as everyone else. They never caught us, but by Friday, they'd ripped out every piece of old intercom equipment and installed a completely new digital system with key cards, passwords, and about 15 different security measures. Our little prank basically forced them to upgrade their entire communication infrastructure. The new system probably cost, like, $50,000

Teachers, what made you punch a student? I was forced to leave the school in handcuffs, but it was worth it, seeing that 15 year old bleed everywhere. When I started teaching at my school district, I noticed that we had a lot of teen moms. We have so many, in fact, that we actually allow them to bring their child to class as part of our inclusive continued education program. As long as the child can stay quiet, they can stay in class. If not, they have to go to the school daycare. Even though we had a lot of teen moms, no one in a million years would have expected that Annie, who had a 4 1 GPA, would come back to school pregnant after summer. Annie was every teacher's favorite student. She was smart, witty, and wasn't the kind of girl that got pushed over. She was a star athlete on the basketball and LaCrosse teams and took a lot of pride in hosting safe parties for everyone. For all we knew, Annie wanted to work for the FBI, and she probably will, too. But when she had her baby, everything tanked. She started sleeping in class, and she was barely coasting by academically because she was so tired that she never got the time to study. All of her friends who were jealous of her, suddenly all turned on her and beat her down over the fact that she's a teen mom. As her homeroom teacher, I did my very best to make sure that I was always on her side, no matter what. I came to school with baby food stocked in a mini fridge, diapers in my drawer, and little rattles for the baby to play with. Even though I did my best to give her support, her classmates made it impossible, especially what they did to her on Halloween. During Halloween, we usually have our quarterly exams, so that means everyone's studying extra hard to pass. Unfortunately, Annie is an overachiever, so she tried to study harder than usual to get her usual grades, but that took a massive nose dive. During lunchtime time, she fell asleep while feeding her baby, and when she woke up from the bell, her baby was gone. What's the strangest rule your family had that made no sense until you Learned the real reason? My family had this super weird rule that I never understood until years later. We were never allowed to use the front door of our house. Like, ever. Not for anything, not when leaving for school, not when friends came over, not even when we ordered pizza. Everyone had to use the side door that LED through our mudroom into the kitchen. T B H. It was embarrassing of as a kid, when friends would come over, they'd naturally walk up to the front door and I'd have to awkwardly redirect them like, oh, no, sorry, we don't use that door. And they'd give me the weirdest looks. I remember when I was like eight, my friend Amara came over for the first time and went straight to the front door. My mom saw through the window and literally ran to intercept her before she could ring the doorbell. She practically dragged her around to the side entrance while giving this awkward explanation about family tradition and house rules. Poor Amara looked so confused and probably thought we were in some weird cult or something. Lol. The front door wasn't broken or anything. It was a perfectly normal door with a deadbolt and everything. Sometimes I catch my mom staring at it with this weird sad expression, but when I asked about it, she changed the subject super fast. My dad was even More intense about it. If any of us kids even joked about using the front door, he'd get this scary, serious look and say, we never use that door. End of discussion. The side door thing became such a huge part of our family identity that I just accepted it as normal after a while. Like, I stopped questioning it. Our house was on a corner lot, so the side door faced the street. Anyway, we had this cute little stone path leading to it with solar lights and everything. My parents put a lot of effort into making the side entrance look welcoming, but I still couldn't help wondering about the front door. It was this big mystery in my life. When I turned 16, I had this huge party planned, and I was so stressed about explaining the door thing to all my new high school friends. I finally broke down and begged my parents to just tell me why, so I could have a better explanation than it's just our family rule. We looked at each other for a long time, having one of those silent parent conversations, but they still refused to explain. My brother Joshua thought it was because someone had died there. My sister Brianna was convinced our house used to be a drug den, and there were secret police cameras watching the front door. We came up with all these wild theories, but none of them seemed to fit. The real breaking point, Came when I was 18. My uncle Ryland came to visit with his new wife, who none of us had met before. No one told her about the door rule. She arrived while we were all in the backyard having a BBQ and used the front door. The instant the doorbell rang, my mom dropped an entire plate of food, and my dad knocked over the grill trying to get to the door. It was absolute chaos. By the time they reached the front door, my uncle's wife was already inside, looking completely bewildered at the mess. In the backyard. She could see through the window. My mom burst into tears and ran to her bedroom. My dad just stood there frozen, staring at the open front door like he was seeing a ghost. My uncle looked so confused and kept asking what was happening. But my dad just quietly closed the door and took everyone back outside. That night, I heard my parents fighting for the first time ever. My mom was crying and saying, it's been almost 20 years, Frank. Maybe it's time to let it go. My dad kept saying, I can't. I just can't. I had never heard him sound so broken. I left for college a few months later, and the door mystery was still unsolved. Every time I came home for breaks, we still used the side door. It had been 19 years of this nonsense, and I was determined to finally get answers. Last Christmas break, I decided I couldn't take it anymore. I sat both my parents down and told them I wasn't leaving until they explained the front door rule. I was an adult now and deserve to know what they told me. Absolutely broke.

As your parents were failing you. When I was 11, my mom trusted me with all her heart. Because by that age, I had already Learned how to do my own laundry, how to cook a meal with only three ingredients, and how to wrap a tight blanket around myself at night. So it felt like someone was holding me. And it's not like my mom was absent from the home or anything. She just spent all her time locked in her room working on her art. And as for why her art was never enough to pay the bills, I just figured that she trusted me enough to make budget friendly choices. So even when I woke up in the middle of the night to gumshots or the 100 degree heat in summer, because we had no a C, I felt a sense of deep pride. And whenever I went to my friends houses, I always cooked the entire house dinner. And they'd wake up to the house SPIC and span. Counters wiped, sofas hovered, even got the dollar bills that fell in between the cushions. They'd always say things like, wow, your mom must be an incredible woman with how well she raised you. And I'd respond with a huge beaming smile. Yes is the best. No one ever questioned why I was so underweight, why I wasn't able to sleep in a bed and instead always opted for the hardwood floor. Why I couldn't even get through a Sentence without apologizing. Always just thought I was mature and polite. So one day, when my mom came out of her room for the first time in days, I lunged towards her. Mommy, look at my report card. The teacher said I did really good. That's nice, honey, she said with a sigh, her tobacco breath burning my nostrils. You tell Mommy what day it is. Wednesday. I thought if I could make myself seem cheery enough, then she would finally love me in the way I wanted. Until suddenly she started thrashing around the place and punched a hole in the drywall. Fuck! Fuck, fuck, fuck! I thought it was effing Thursday. I thought the payout was today. When I walked up to her, she lifted her fist as if she was about to take her anger out on me. So I made sure to speak really quickly. Mom, I have 20 bucks. Immediately her face softened. Honey, you are the kindest, most mature girl a mother could ever ask for. But I didn't have time to save her the moment, because as soon as she snatched it from my hand, she walked over to the store to buy art supplies, came home, and went back to working on her art. Now, you may be wondering where I got the $20 from. Well, there was this rich kid at school who always had lunch money. He was mean to everyone anyway, hitting on kids that looked poor. I started To keep a mental record of who I could take from and when. All for those brief moments when mom would emerge eating another $20, another $40, another fix of her art supplies. And like all preteens breaking the law, I got cocky. And after just three months, Miss Lee caught me. I already knew what was going down when she called me into her office. Thought she was going to call the police or at least scream at me. But no. Instead, she asked me questions. Not an interrogation, more like making conversation. Her what's your favourite food? Me rice with ketchup. Her what do you and your mom like to do for fun together? Me sometimes, the day after she gets her government check and she does art in her room, I sit by the crack in her door and talk about my day. Her what time do you go to sleep at? Me at 2:00am, when my mom goes quiet. The entire time, I had a smile on my face. Just happy to talk to an adult that cared about me. But when I looked up, I saw it, her eyes filled with tears. She told me to wait there while she went to go get someone, and handed me a Nintendo Switch to keep me occupied. And two hours later, I heard a knock on the door. It wasn't just Miss Lee, because it was Miss Lee with two police officers and a lady in a Suit who said she was from Family Services? They all had the same look, like they were trying to smile but couldn't quite manage it. Sweetie, we're going to take a ride to your house. The lady said we need to check on your mom. I began hyperventilating. No!

Strangest gift you've ever received that still warmed your heart? My grandpa gave me a bag of rocks for my 15th birthday, and I thought he'd finally lost it. I'm talking about literal rocks, not gems, not crystals, just regular gray and brown rocks he'd apparently collected from his backyard. They came in a crumpled paper bag with happy birthday, Becca written in his shaky handwriting. My parents looked mortified. My little brother Jake started laughing until mom elbowed him, thanks, Grandpa. I and trying not to sound disappointed. I mean, my friends got cars and iPhones for their birthdays. I got geological samples. Grandpa just winked and said, you'll figure it out, kiddo. For weeks, that bag sat on my desk, mocking me. I'd moved out most of my childhood stuff to make room for more mature decorations, but somehow those rocks stayed. Every time I looked at them, I wondered if Grandpa was developing dementia or if this was some weird test. Then one night, I was stressed about this massive history project that was due the next day. I procrastinated until the last minute, and I was panicking about how I was going to research the entire Civil War in one night. I grabbed one of grandpa's rocks without thinking and started fidgeting with it while I read. Something felt different about it. There were tiny ridges I hadn't noticed before. I held it up to my desk lamp and almost dropped it. There were letters carved Into the surface, tiny, barely visible letters that spelled look closer. My heart started racing. I dumped the entire bag onto my bed and examined each rock under my lamp. Every single one had something carved into it. Some had single letters, others had numbers, and a few had tiny symbols that looked like arrows. It took me three hours to figure out it was a puzzle. Numbers corresponded to letters in the alphabet, and the arrows showed the order. When I finally decoded everything, I had an address I didn't recognize and the words your real birthday present. The address LED me to a storage unit across town. Grandpa was waiting there the next Saturday with the key and the biggest grin I'd ever seen on his face. Inside

Most innocent favour you've done that completely backfired. I was just trying to be a good uncle, but apparently that's how you end up in handcuffs. My sister Maria called me that Tuesday morning while I was still in bed after working a night shift at the hospital. Her voice sounded panicked and she was talking so fast I could barely understand her. She had some emergency medical procedure and needed me to pick up her daughter Emma from school. I hadn't seen my niece in, like, six months because I lived across town and work had been crazy. Maria texted me the details before her phone died. Emma Johnson, Missus Patterson's class. Purple backpack. I dragged myself out of bed and drove to the elementary school at dismissal time. The place was absolute chaos, with hundreds of kids in those navy blue uniforms running everywhere. I walked into the office trying to look confident, even though I felt like I was about to pass out from exhaustion. I'm here to pick up Emma Johnson, told the secretary, who was juggling three phone calls and barely looked up at me. She typed something into her computer and buzzed a classroom. A few minutes later, this little blonde girl with a purple backpack walked into the office. She seemed kind of shy, but followed me when I said her mom sent me to get her. The car ride was pretty quiet at first. My niece gave me these short answers. When I tried to make conversation, so I figured she was just tired. After school, I remembered Maria saying something about promising Emma ice cream if she was good, so I stopped at McDonald's. My niece perked up immediately and started chatting about her art project while eating her cone. We got to Maria's house, and I used the spare key under the fake rock to let us in. The house was empty since Maria was still at the hospital. I made my niece a snack and helped her with her math homework. It was actually pretty sweet when she warmed up to me. We worked on multiplication tables for a while, and then she wanted to show me her drawings. Three hours passed and everything seemed fine until my niece looked at me with these confused eyes and said, when are we going to my house? My stomach dropped. This is your house, sweetie. She shook her head. No, it's not. I live on a different street with the big tree in front. That's when everything went sideways. I tried calling Maria, but her phone was still dead. The kids started crying. I was trying to calm her down when I heard cars screeching outside. I looked through the window and saw police cars everywhere with officers pointing weapons at the house. Come out with your hands up! Someone shouted through a megaphone. The little girl ran to the door, screaming, she took me! She took me! The officers rushed In and threw me on the ground, my face pressed against Maria's carpet, while they cuffed my hands behind my back. The neighbors were all outside watching from their porches. I tried explaining, but the cops kept telling me to save it for the detectives. The interrogation room at the police station smelled like old coffee and despair. Two detectives grilled me for hours while I sat there in those metal handcuffs. They asking why I took the child and where I was planning to go. I told them over and over about Maria's call and the school pickup, but they weren't buying it. The detective with the mustache rolled his eyes and called the school, but of course, the office was closed. The principal wasn't answering her phone, and the secretary had gone home for the day. They showing me security footage of me taking Ann Emma Johnson, but there was no way to tell which one until morning. Then the door flew open and Maria burst in, still wearing her hospital gown with those paper

Have you ever hated your own child? I never thought I would. Until I discovered what my son was doing to pay for his little sister's cancer treatment. Emma was only 6 when she was diagnosed with acute lymphoblastic leukemia. The bills were crushing us. $15,000 a month, even with insurance. I worked three jobs. Warehouse, gas station, weekend construction. My wife cleaned offices after her grocery store shift. We were drowning. My 16 year old son, Jake had always been responsible. Honor roll, varsity baseball, never any trouble. But after Emma's diagnosis, he started acting strange. He came home with expensive gifts for Emma. American Girl dolls, Nintendo games, bags of her favorite organic gummy bears. When I asked where he got the money, he mumbled something about odd jobs for neighbors. Mowing lawns, walking dogs. I wanted to believe him. We needed any help we could get. The gifts kept coming. A two hundred dollar tablet so Emma could watch movies during chemo. Designer pajamas to replace the gown she hated. A stuffed elephant that cost more than groceries. I got suspicious. But Emma smile when she got those gifts. That was her only light. Then her treatment got worse. Standard chemo wasn't working. Her doctor recommended an experimental drug. $50,000 up front. Insurance wouldn't cover it. I spent three days calling every charity, foundation, begging for help. Nothing. At 2:00am, I sat at the kitchen table, calculator in hand, figuring out if we could get a second Mortgage. When Jake walked in, his eyes were red. He handed me a vanilla envelope for Emma's treatment. I opened it. Stacks of cash, all of it. $50,000. Where the hell did you get this? I demanded. He wouldn't meet my eyes. Does it matter? Emma needs it. It matters to me, Jake. Where did this money come from? He stood there, tears falling. I can't tell you. The next day, I followed him. Called in sick. Watched as he walked past the buses and student lot. A black Mercedes pulled up. The driver looked 40 in a tailored suit. Jake got in. I froze. Three hours later, the same card

You ever accidentally joined the wrong group chat and just stayed? A few months ago, I got added to a group chat called Wedding Squad. I assumed it was for my cousin's wedding. The names looked familiar. There was a Jess, a Tori, even a Mike. All names I vaguely recognized from family stuff, so I stayed. At first it was just casual dress choices, travel plans, someone asking if they should bring deviled eggs. I liked the vibe. No drama, lots of memes. I even I'm in once with we're not doing a bouquet toss, right? Because last time I caught it and tore my ACL. Everyone laughed. Just even replied, classic you. Cool. I was fitting in. Weeks go by and I'm deep in this wedding. Now I'm voting on flower arrangements, helping plan the Bachelorette weekend, and arguing that Mike should not wear Crocs with his suit. Then one day, someone finally asks, wait, who's this number? Silence, panicked, and said, it's me. You know, from the cabin. Jess asked, wait, are you Laura's cousin? I replied, no. Should I be? Turns out I was never supposed to be in the group. Whole different family, whole different wedding. They'd meant to add a different band, but here's the kicker. They invited me anyway. I showed up, sat between two uncles I'd never met, danced with Aunt Marcy, even gave a toast. No one questioned it. Laura hugged me at the end and said, band number two, you're One of us now. Still in the group chat. By the way. We're planning a baby shower now.

Something your family always celebrated privately that other families do publicly. In my family, we did what we called Passing Day every year on June 11th. It wasn't like a normal Celebration with cake and presents. We'd wake up at 3:00am exactly. My dad would play this really specific song from the 70s about surviving, and we'd all gather in the living room wearing white. Mom would lay out this old Polaroid of my Uncle Roland, who died before I was born, and we'd all have to touch it. My dad would make us all drink this nasty smoothie thing that was, like tomato juice and raw eggs and some other stuff I never knew. He said it was life force, but it made me gag every time. The rule was you couldn't stop drinking until the song ended. The weirdest part was we couldn't talk about passing day to anyone outside our house. Not even my grandparents knew we did this. I found out in middle school that normal families just have, like, regular birthdays and anniversaries. I guess the worst part was the isolation room. After the smoothie thing, we'd each have to spend exactly one hour alone in a dark closet. Dad called it the void and said it was to help us understand what Uncle Rowland went through. As a kid, I was terrified of the dark and would sob the entire time. But dad said that was part of it, that I needed to feel the Fear to appreciate being alive. When I got older, I started asking questions, like why we celebrated someone dying in such a weird way. Mom would get all quiet and dad would get super intense, saying I didn't understand what a gift it was to be here. I remember him grabbing my shoulders once when I was 15, and I was, like, crying because I wanted to sleep over at Miranda's house on passing day. He looked at me with these wild eyes and said passing day was the only reason I existed. I think that was when I started to realise something was off. Miranda's family just had normal traditions, like Christmas and Thanksgiving. They didn't make her drink disgusting smoothies or lock her in closets or wake up at weird times. They didn't have pictures of dead relatives they had to touch. I spent years being so confused about it all. Sometimes I try to ask about Uncle Rowland, like how he died or why we did all this stuff. Mom would just say he passed over, which told me nothing. Dad would get this distant look and say, Rowland sacrificed everything for our family. It was all so dramatic and vague. When I turned 18, I refused to do passing day. Dad went ballistic, like, full on screaming that I was ungrateful and didn't deserve what Rowland had given us. Mom just cried in the corner, which made me feel like shit, but I couldn't do it. Anymore, I stood my ground, and dad actually locked me out of the house. I had to stay with Miranda that night. The next day, mom called me crying, saying I needed to come home. When I got there, dad was acting like nothing happened. It was so messed up. He just casually asked if I wanted breakfast, like he hadn't kicked me out the night before. After that, I moved out as fast as I could, got an apartment with Kayla, and tried to put some distance between me and my family's weirdness. I'd still visit sometimes, but I made sure it was never around June 11th. The thing is, I still couldn't stop thinking about Uncle Rowland and what really happened. Why did we have this bizarre ritual around his death? Why was my dad so obsessed with it? Why couldn't we talk about it last year? I finally got the courage to ask my grandma about him. We were having coffee, and I just casually mentioned Roland's name. She got this confused look and was like, who? Which blew my mind, because this was supposedly her son who died. I tried to explain about Dad's brother Roland, who passed away before I was born. Grandma looked seriously concerned and told me my dad was an only child. I never heard of any Roland in the family. I felt like I was going crazy. I went home and dug through old family albums looking for that Polaroid we used. During passing day, I couldn't find it anywhere. I was seriously starting to think I'd imagine the whole thing. Maybe passing day was some elaborate game my dad made up. But why would he invent a fake dead brother? A few weeks later, I found this old box hidden behind some insulation. Inside was the Polaroid of Uncle Roland. But it wasn't a picture of a man. It was a picture of a little boy, maybe 7 or 8 years old. And written on the back was Cody, age 8. Summer Camp, 1985. Cody is my dad's name. There were other things in the box, too. I didn't have time to read it all, but I took some pictures with my phone when my parents weren't looking. That night, I read through what I captured. The journal was my dad's from when he was a kid. Apparently, he had a near drowning experience at camp when he was 8. He was underwater for over four minutes and was technically dead before they resuscitated him. The time of the incident, 3:00am. The date, June 11th. Everything started making sense in the most twisted way. There was no Uncle Roland. Roland was what my

What? Nickname seems sweet as a kid, but hit different when you got older. So growing up, everyone in my family called me mittens. My mom, dad, both brothers, even my grandma. It was constant, mittens, come eat, mittens, clean your room. Where's mittens? I just assumed it was a quirky little pet name. I mean, I liked cats. I had tiny hands as a kid, so I figured it was something sweet about that. I even had a onesie with cat mittens sewn on it that I wore into elementary school. My lunch box said mittens. I had no reason to question it. It was just me. The nickname stuck all through childhood and into my teens. Teachers at parent night would call me mittens because that's what my parents wrote on my lunch containers. Didn't mind. I thought it was unique. At sleepovers, my friends would tease me about it, but I just shrugged it off. It's just what my family calls me. But deep down, I always kind of wondered why. There was no origin story, no cute moment that kicked it off. Just always been. I remember one day in seventh grade, my older brother brought a friend over, and the friend heard my mom call out, mittens, dinner! He paused and asked my brother, why do you call her that? My brother just grinned and said, it's a long story. Then they both started laughing. I was like, what? What's funny? But they waved me Off? Nothing. It's just a cute name. I dropped it, but it stuck in my head for years. Fast forward to high school. I'm a sophomore, and we're doing this icebreaker activity in Spanish class where we have to share our childhood nicknames and what they meant. I proudly told the class that mine was mittens and that it was because I had little hands and liked cats. That's when this kid, Tyler in the back, snorted and whispered something to the guy next to him. The teacher didn't hear, but I did. Bet she doesn't know what that really means. It bothered me all day. I went home and googled it. Nothing came up except, well, actual mittens. Still, it stirred something in me. I started casually asking family members about the nickname. Everyone deflected. My mom said, you were just such a cozy baby. And my grandma said, your hands were so warm. But my brothers would exchange these smug looks and crack up when I brought it up. Then two Christmases ago, I finally found out. I was 24 and home for the holidays. We were doing our usual gift exchange, and I got a big box from my dad. Inside a

The pettiest rule your school ever tried to enforce. My school installed five minute bathroom timers because they thought kids were vaping in there. I'm Ella, and I was a junior when our principal announced this genius plan. Every bathroom stall got these little digital timers that started counting down the second you lock the door. Five minutes and one second. Boom! Automatic email to your parents and the principal saying you were misusing school facilities. He claimed it was about vaping, but honestly, half the girls in my grade have stomach problems or heavy periods. Imagine trying to explain to your mom why you got flagged for taking six minutes to change a pad. Pure humiliation. The first week was chaos. Kids were literally running out of bathrooms with their pants half up because they heard the timer beeping. My friend Jessica got detention because she had food poisoning and couldn't finish in time. The email to her parents said she was loitering with intent to engage in prohibited activities. Her mom thought she was doing drugs. That's when I decided this was war. I grabbed my old walkie talkie from when I was obsessed with spy movies and called up my friends Maya and Zoe. We met at lunch and I laid out the plan. Bathroom relay team. I explained drawing diagrams on a napkin. One person goes in, starts the timer, hands off the walkie at 4 minutes, 30 seconds. Next person walks in and takes over. Timer resets, bathroom never gets empty. Nobody goes over five minutes. Maya thought I was insane, so he was immediately in. We started small, just the three of us rotating through the second floor girls bathroom. During lunch. I made us a little notebook titled Bathroom Attendance Team, Clean Cheeks. We logged every shift change. We felt like secret agents. Day one worked perfectly. Day two, the sophomore named Brianna noticed us whispering by the bathroom door and asked what was up. I figured, what the hell and explained the plan. She was so excited, she literally clapped. By day three, we had seven girls. By the end of the week, it was like 20 kids rotating through bathroom duty. Kids were doing homework by the sinks during their shifts. This freshman named Tyler brought a camping chair and set up a whole study station by the mirrors. The whole thing was getting ridiculous. Kids were signing up for bathroom shifts like it was a job. We had a waiting list. People were trading shifts like they were concert tickets. The funniest part, nobody was vaping anymore because the bathrooms were never empty. Mission accomplished, right? Wrong. The administration lost their minds when they realized kids were lining up for bathroom duty instead of going to class. The maintenance guy complained that students were treating the bathrooms like a library. One teacher tried to give detention to a girl who is clearly just washing her hands for the 15th time. That day, Principal Johnson called me to the office after two weeks. I sat there with my notebook, flipping through pages of our shift schedules. Miss Patterson, this is creative, he said, looking tired, but you're disrupting the educational environment. I just stared at him. Sir, you installed timers in the bathrooms? We're following your rules. Nobody's going over five minutes. He rubbed

Ex alcoholics. What made you stop drinking? When I was 16, my whole family died in a car accident. I was the only one who made it. One second, we were driving home from my sister's soccer game, laughing at something dumb. The next, I woke up in a hospital bed with a doctor standing over me, looking like he didn't want to be the one to say it. After that, I shut down. I had no close family, so they put me in foster care. The people who took me in barely acknowledged me. They made me sleep in the shed when I pissed them off. Some nights, I went to bed hungry. I started sneaking out, getting strangers to buy me whatever cheap liquor I could get my hands on. By 18, I was homeless. My routine was simple. Wake up, go to work, buy booze, pass out, eat. I had no reason to stop. I didn't care if I woke up the next morning or not. Then one night, I was drinking outside a gas station when a cop pulled up. I kept my head down, waiting for him to tell me to move or arrest me. Instead, he leaned against his car and said, you even old enough for that? I shrugged. Yeah, basically. He looked at me for a second, then nodded toward his car. Get in. I figured, what the hell? Maybe a night in a cell would be better than this. But he Didn't take me to the station. He went inside the gas station and returned with a coffee and a bag of food. He handed them to me and said, eat. I stared at the bag. It had been a while since someone told me to eat like they actually cared. I didn't say much, but he got me to talk. I told him I had no one, no home, nothing. Listened. Then told me to wait at the station until his shift ended. That night, he brought me to his place. Couch is yours, he said, tossing me a blanket. We'll figure things out in the morning. I don't know why, but I told him everything. My family, the drinking, the foster home. He just nodded like none of it surprised him. Then he told me he lost his wife in a car accident, too. Said he got it. He didn't try to fix me. He didn't lecture me. He just helped. Took me to get a new I D. Since mine was long gone. Helped me get a better job. Kept his fridge stocked and told me to eat whatever I wanted. If I disappeared for days on a Bender, he didn't yell. He just said, you done? When I stumbled back through the door one time, he found me passed out in my car and didn't say a word. Just opened the door, pulled me up and walked me inside. Sat me down at the kitchen table and Put a plate of food in front of me. I could barely keep my eyes open. But I remember him saying, you keep doing this, you're gonna end up like the guys I scrape off the sidewalk at 3:00am. Laughed. Maybe that's the plan. He didn't laugh. Just shook his head and said, nah, not you. I didn't believe him, but something about the way he said it stuck with me. One day he came home and said, listen, I can get you into a program. Law enforcement. You just gotta sober up first. I wanted to say yes. I wanted to believe I could do it. But I couldn't. I told him no. Then one night, he didn't come home. The next morning, I saw the headline. Cop was shot in the line of duty. My stomach dropped. I ran to the hospital and pushed past the nurses until I found his room. He was unconscious, hooked up to machines. They said he'd live, but he'd need help. I told them I'd do it. For weeks.

Dream workers. What's the most disturbing thing you've ever seen? I work at Smash Zone downtown, and let me tell you, we get all kinds of weirdos. People come in to break stuff when they're pissed about divorces, job losses, whatever. But this one guy from last month still gives me chills. It was a Tuesday afternoon, super slow. This dude walks in wearing a wrinkled button up shirt and jeans that looked like he'd slept in them. He's got these balloons tied around his wrist. Cheap kind from dollar stores. Red, blue, yellow. Real cheerful looking. Hey there, he says with this big smile. I'd like your basic package, please. I'm thinking, okay, birthday boy wants to blow off some steam. Happens all the time. But then I noticed his hands are shaking as he fills out the waiver. Not nervous, shaking like he'd been drinking too much coffee for three days straight. Actually, he says, looking up from the paperwork, can I bring my own stuff to smash? I've got some personal items. We allow it sometimes if it's safe. He pulls out this beat up shoebox from a backpack. Inside there's random junk. An old digital clock with a cracked screen, a Superman lunch box that's all dented up, and maybe six or seven VHS tapes. Nothing dangerous, he says, reading my face. Just some old memories I need to get rid of. I check everything over. No glass, no chemicals, nothing sharp. Just weird old stuff. That smelled like basement storage. Can I get the room with the brick wall? He asks. The one that echoes really good? That's room three. Most people want the padded rooms because they're quieter, but whatever. I suit him up in safety gear and show him in. Here's where it got freaky. I always watch through the window for safety reasons. Usually people go nuts immediately. Screaming, crying, throwing stuff around like maniacs. This guy, dead silent. He picks up the alarm clock first, holds it like it weighs 50 pounds. Then he starts whispering to it. I can't hear what he's saying through the glass, but his lips are moving the whole time. After maybe two minutes of this, he raises it over his head and smashes it against the brick wall. Same thing with the lunch box. Whispers to it, then destroys it with the baseball bat. We provide the V H S. Tapes. He crushes one by one under his boot, still talking to each one before he destroys it. The whole thing takes him maybe 20 minutes. I'm starting to think he's done when he reaches into the box one more time. He pulls out a piece of paper. Even from the window, I can tell it's a kid's drawing. You know how they look with those thick crayon lines and stick figures. He unfolds it real careful and just stares at it for 10 solid minutes. This guy stands there holding the straw, not moving. Barely breathing, I'm starting to wonder if I should check on him when he suddenly folds it back up, sets it on the little table in the middle of the room, and walks out. All done, he says, like nothing happened, pays in cash, tips me 20 bucks, and leaves with those stupid balloons still tied to his wrist. Go in to clean up the room, and it's trashed. Bits of plastic and metal everywhere. But that drawing is sitting perfectly folded on the table, untouched. I almost threw it away, but something felt wrong about it, so I stuck it in our lost and found box instead. Three hours later, two cops show up.

My coworker is heterophobic. I work as a power plant turbine engineer in New York City. For two years straight, it was just me and seven other dudes on the team until Ashley joined. She talked in a high pitched voice and wore a very obvious push up bra, so I was scared of her being a pick me. But she ended up being super nice, so much so that I invited her to our weekly team bonding session. So there we were, all nine of us, sitting in a dumpling house, when she pointed out a girl that walked in. Hey, she seems like she would be your type. You guys would look so cute together. I stared at her blankly, and that's when Joshua, my team leader, chimed in. OMG, Amanda! My name! I told you dressing emo made you look a little fruity. I laughed awkwardly and told Ashley that I was, in fact, a heterosexual woman. At first she laughed along with me and even exclaimed that we could go hunting for husbands together. But from there, whenever I spoke to her in the group, she'd act like she didn't hear me. And whenever me and Joshua tried to talk to each other, she would cut me off and try to overpower the conversation. Usually at work. She trusted everything that I told her and seemed to have a lot of respect for me. But throughout the entire week she kept making passive aggressive comments about how Some of us had to earn our spots through actual qualifications. And on all the days that Joshua was meant to be in the office, she would wear pencil skirts that were too see through to be by accident. Until this point, I thought she had a crush on Joshua and was just trying to get his attention. But I was sitting in the bathroom stall, procrastinating work and playing Candy Crush when I heard it. Ashley stormed in, screaming her head off on a phone call. Sure, Amanda's nice and all, but I'm just sick of everyone pretending that it's normal that she got promoted in six months as if she actually has any skill. And suddenly everything made sense, because that's when she said, as if that asshole has ever done any work outside of Joshua's bedroom, you effing idiot! Joshua is gay!
