Then she made her biggest mistake. She looked at Tyler and said, Tyler's make sure you study hard in school so you don't end up like your daddy, okay? The table went dead silent. Jake's face turned red. Mom literally gasped. Dad put down his fork and just stared at Emma. But Tyler. Tyler just looked up from his mashed potatoes, blinked those big innocent eyes, and said in the sweetest voice ever, Aunt Emma, why?

We were watching a movie and my phone lit up with another text from my sister in law telling me she was now going to be here at one PM the next day to swim with Chloe. My husband saw it and told me to tell her not to come. This is really weird behavior for my husband because he tends to do anything to accommodate my sister in law and very rarely refuses her anything. I asked him if something had happened and he shrugged it off and we kept watching the movie. A few minutes later he paused the movie and said he wanted to ask me a question. He asked if I'd noticed Chloe never swam when she came to our house. I wish I could say I was calm and collected. I ended up laughing hysterically. I was honestly just so relieved he brought it up instead of me having to be the one to do it. I think my husband thought I was losing my mind. When I finally stopped laughing, he repeated the question and said he wanted a serious answer. I said of course I've noticed, and he awkwardly replied, so you must have noticed the other thing too. To summarize the conversation that followed, my husband hadn't noticed Chloe was flirting with him the first few days because he was so busy with work he wasn't really paying attention to anything else. He said when she started getting hasty is when he Suddenly had the light bulb moment that she was into him. He says he didn't want to unnecessarily stress me out, so he never mentioned anything, but he was worried I'd noticed too and thought he was interested because he hadn't immediately shut it down. He did privately speak to Chloe and told her he was happily married and wasn't interested in starting anything with anyone else. Apparently she never took him seriously because she kept doing it. In the end, he called his sister on Sunday to tell her either she got her to stop or Chloe couldn't come over anymore. His sister ended up having a tantrum and said a few nasty things about me. She insisted I was somehow behind his request and made some comments about how I was controlling and insecure because I looked like a beached whale and Chloe was younger and hotter. She then claimed I had baby trapped him, and when my husband pointed out we were already married so I didn't need to trap him, and that he was the one who wanted to start a family, she kept insisting I had manipulated him into feeling that way. The thing that made my husband finally snap was when she said the baby was already ruining everything and it was just going to get worse when it was born and he should have dragged me to the termination clinic whilst he had the chance. He told her that neither her nor Chloe Were welcome in our home anymore. Until they apologized for how they've been behaving and for the things my sister in law said. Apparently she started crying and said she was sorry, that she didn't mean it, and she was just scared to lose him. And that she wasn't thinking clearly. He hung up on her. He showed me his phone, and she's been calling him and texting him since, begging him to reply.

But family tradition should forever be forgotten. My mom called it truth night. Every month, our whole family sat in a circle. One person had to confess their biggest secret or lie from the past month. If you refuse to share, you got punished. I was eight when it started. My older sister went first. She admitted to breaking Mom's favourite vase and blaming our dog. Mom just nodded and wrote it down in her little black notebook. The first red flag came when my teacher, Missus Williams, called mom about my essay on my family. I'd written about truth night, thinking it was normal. Missus Williams asked if I felt safe at home. And next day, mom pulled me aside and said Missus Williams had misunderstood our beautiful family tradition. And that I needed to be more careful about what I shared with outsiders. That's when mom started coaching us. Before school, she'd practice conversations with us, teaching us exactly what to say if anyone asked about our home life. We're a very close, honest family, she'd make us repeat. Things escalated when my best friend, Tyler, came for a sleepover. Mom insisted he participate in truth night. Tyler looked confused, but confessed to lying about finishing his homework. Mom wrote it down and asked him personal questions about his parents marriage. Tyler never came back to our house. My sister started getting mysterious bruises. When I asked, she said they were from private truth sessions with mom. Apparently, If your monthly confession wasn't deep enough, you got individual meetings where mom would keep pushing until you broke down completely. Dad tried to intervene once. Said truth night was getting out of hand and maybe we should stop. That night, mom made him participate for the first time. She forced him to confess to an affair he'd had five years ago in front of all us kids. He never questioned truth night again. This school counselor, Mister Bennett, started asking me weird questions. Did I feel comfortable talking to my parents? Did I have secrets I couldn't share? I lied and said everything was perfect. But I could tell he didn't believe me. Mom must have suspected, because she started homeschooling us the next week. Now isolated from the outside world, truth night became a daily occurrence. Mom said we needed intensive honesty training since we were no longer getting corrupted by outside influences. My brother started having seizures from the stress. When I begged mom to take him to a doctor, she said his seizures were just his body releasing suppressed lies. Our neighbor, Missus Foster, called child services after hearing my brother screaming during one of his seizures. When the social worker arrived, mom had coached us perfectly. We sat in the living room like perfect children, explaining how much we loved our honesty circles and how they brought our family closer together. The social worker left satisfied, but Missus Foster didn't give up. She started recording The sounds coming from our house. And gathered evidence. One day, she knocked on our door with two police officers. Mom wasn't prepared this time. As the officers questioned us separately, I finally broke. I told them about the daily fashions, the bruises, my brother's seizures, and how terrified we all were. My sister and brother confirmed everything. That's when the real truth came out. While searching mom's room, police found her communications with Doctor Sarah Mitchell from the university psychology department. Mom wasn't just a disturbed

What's a lie your family told you for years that you only found out wasn't true by accident? Okay, so I grew up thinking I was allergic to chocolate. Like, deathly allergic. My parents had me convinced since I was literally a toddler that even the smallest piece would send me into anaphylactic shock. They had this whole system. Special notes to all my teachers, special talks with my friends, parents before sleepovers, the whole nine yards. It affected everything. Birthday parties were a nightmare growing up because everyone else would be eating cake and ice cream while I'd be sitting there with my special treats my mom packed. Halloween was the worst, tbh. I'd go trick or treating with friends, but then have to trade away like 75% of my candy haul for the safe stuff. My mom would literally inspect my entire bag and confiscate anything with even a trace of chocolate. My dad, Donald, was especially strict about it. He'd check restaurant dessert menus before we went anywhere. Would interrogate servers about ingredients. Once he made this huge scene at restaurant because he thought they were lying about whether the vanilla ice cream had been scooped with the same scoop as the chocolate. I was so embarrassed, I wanted to disappear for our. The thing is, I never questioned it. Like, why would I? Parents don't just make up life threatening allergies for their kid. I wore a medical alert bracelet. They kept an Epipen in the House. When I was 12, my mom, Sylvia, made me practice jabbing myself with the trainer pen so I know what to do if I accidentally ate chocolate when she wasn't around. I still remember how serious she looked when she told me, this could save your life one day. Throughout high school, it became part of my identity in this weird way. I was Ava, the girl who'll die if she eats a Hershey's kiss. My friends were super protective, too. Tom, my best friend's boyfriend, once tackled a kid who was trying to dare me to eat a chocolate chip cookie as a joke. Everyone treated it like this deadly serious thing because that's what my parents had told them. I never even questioned it until I was 27. 27 years old. Can you believe that? Like, I went through my entire childhood, teen years, college, halfway through my 20s, believing I had this life threatening condition. So here's how I found out. I was at this work conference in Chicago, staying at a hotel. After a long day of boring presentations, I got back to my room, and there was this little chocolate mint on my pillow. I was exhausted and not really paying attention, and I just ate it without thinking. It was in my mouth before I even realized what I was doing. And then it hit me. I just eaten chocolate. My heart started racing immediately. I ran to the bathroom looking for hives. Or swelling, waiting for my throat to close up. I was freaking out, like, literally on the floor of this hotel bathroom having a full blown panic attack. I called the front desk screaming about needing an ambulance because I was having an allergic reaction. The paramedics came super fast. They checked all my vitals, looked at my skin, monitored my breathing, and nothing, absolutely nothing was happening. One of them asked if I was sure I was allergic to chocolate. I told them about my lifelong severe allergy, and they were like, have you ever actually had a reaction before? And I realized, no, I hadn't because my parents have been so careful. I'd never actually eaten chocolate before. The paramedics suggested I might wanna get an allergy test done just to be sure. They were super nice about it, but I could tell they thought I was overreacting. I was so embarrassed. After they left, I sat there for hours just trying to process everything. The next day, I called my doctor back home and explained what happened. She was confused because there was nothing about a chocolate allergy in my medical records. Nothing. She agreed to schedule allergy testing. When I got back, two weeks later, I'm sitting in an allergist office getting tested for chocolate allergies. The results? Absolutely nothing. No allergic response whatsoever. The doctor looked confused and asked who had diagnosed me originally. When I said my parents, she gave me this look. I'll Never forget. I confronted my parents that weekend. I was shaking when I told them what happened. I expected them to be shocked or confused, but instead, my mom just started crying. My dad got all quiet and weird. Then he finally said, we never thought you'd actually eat it. Turns out, when I was three, my older brother Hector had died. I barely remember him, but apparently he had a severe peanut allergy and died from anaphylaxis after accidentally eating something with peanuts at a birthday party. My parents were absolutely devastated. After he died, they became obsessed with protecting me. But instead of just being normally cautious parents, they decided to tell me I was deathly allergic to chocolate, something they could easily control and keep away from me. They thought if I believed I had a deadly allergy, I'd be more careful about what I ate in general.

Worker looked down on me, not knowing I was his boss. I own a franchise that my family started when I was younger. I was the only one who wanted to take over the family business, so my father ended up giving it to me. My father gave me two restaurants before he passed away, and currently I have 12 restaurants. I hired my family members, including my nephews and my kids, to manage my stores so they can learn to expand the family business when I'm gone. I never forced them to manage my restaurants, but I showed them my wealth when they were teenagers and explained that if they wanted the lifestyle and comfort I had, I was giving them the opportunity to achieve it. All of them understood that if they wanted to have a piece of my restaurants, they had to learn how to be entrepreneurs and run a business. My oldest son, 30, manages four stores. My daughter, 28, owns three stores. My youngest, 24, two stores, and my nephew, 26, three stores. I'm proud of what they've accomplished, and I feel very confident that my hard work will be taken care of when I'm no longer here. Every now and then, I like to visit one of my restaurants randomly to ensure that everything is up to their standards and running correctly. I'm a simple guy and have no interest in buying expensive clothes to impress others. My family even says that if they Didn't know me. I'd fit in with the homeless people. I opened the door and waited in the lobby with three other people who had families. All of them except me were taken care of and seated within the next five minutes. I waited and one waitress looked at me and continued walking, grinning. Next thing you know, another waitress walked past me and ignored me, and now two families had come in and both waitresses seated them. At this point, I was shocked and completely speechless about what I was witnessing, especially since my restaurants are known for having excellent customer service. I got tired and decided to go up and ask the same waitress if I could be seated. Her smile faded away and she gave me an annoyed look when I stopped her. After saying excuse me, I apologized and asked when I would be seated because I had been waiting patiently for more than 45 minutes. The waitress, still annoyed, looked at me and told me to wait patiently while someone would come to seat me. Five minutes later, another family came in and asked to be seated, and the same waitress immediately took them to an empty table. At the this point, I knew she was judging me based on my appearance and I was getting frustrated. I decided I didn't want to waste any more time and left the restaurant ten minutes later. I left fuming with anger, never having felt so disrespected in My life. I decided to come back 30 minutes before closing, around the time my son usually returns to the store to do paperwork. When I walked in, first thing I saw was the same waitress in the lobby. She saw me and gave me the biggest side eye full of attitude. She scoffed and said, you again? Didn't you get the hint the first time? Again, I was shocked and said, excuse me? Do you not know how to treat people with respect? She looked even more annoyed and said, listen, old man, we're about to close and this restaurant doesn't serve, you know, people who dress like you. I was completely speechless and angry, to the point where I even started getting mad at my son for hiring this girl. I had had enough. Just as I was about to start yelling, my son walked by and said, dad, what are you doing here? I looked at him angrily and said, who the hell is this girl, and how the hell did you manage to hire someone so disrespectful? My son, already looking worried, tried to calm me down and then turned to the waitress in a quiet, serious tone. My son looked at her and said, my office now. I had some time to calm myself down, and as I walked into my son's office, I looked at the waitress and said, I want your friend here too. I hadn't forgotten about

You love your mom. When my girlfriend slapped me across the face for the first time, it hurt a lot. But I thought it was just something all girlfriends did. So I just laughed it off and told her not to do it again. Because other than that, she was my dream girl. Cook me homemade chicken Alfredo whenever I was sad. She was the first girl to ever get me flowers. And even six months into the relationship, when I paid for our meals together, she's just as grateful as she was on our first date. Plus, it wasn't until eight months into our relationship that flip had switched, because it was around this time that she found out her dad had been cheating on her mom. It started off small. She'd grab my phone when I got texts just to check who it was. She'd get upset if I talked to my godmother about a book she wrote. You don't need to smile that much when you talk to her. She'd say about the cashier at target. Then came the accusations. If I was five minutes late from work, I was cheating. If I didn't answer her texts immediately, I was with another girl. She'd slap me playfully when other women walked by, but her nails would leave marks when I mentioned it hurt. She'd cry about how I didn't understand what she was going through with her family falling apart. Then came the night where Stella pushed Me off the balcony. Luckily, I lived on the first floor of my apartment building. I was just left with two broken ribs and a dislocated shoulder. When I went to the hospital, I told all the nurses that I had just played too much basketball. the other people in my life were already really suspicious of stuff, so I didn't tell them either. But no matter how much she cried to the doctors or posted about how proud she was of me, there was one woman who wasn't buying into her BS, and that woman was my stepmom. She showed up at my apartment the next day with groceries and her laptop. I'm starting a YouTube channel. She announced home organization and cleaning tips. Barry Marie condo meets suburban mom. I thought she lost her mind. She was a tax attorney who could barely operate the TV remote. She sort of gilded me into being her co host using the I pushed you out of me card. And she set up cameras all around my apartment. The bathroom, the kitchen, even my bedroom. At the time, she claimed it was so our audience could get the full experience. The genius part. Stella thought it was pathetic. Desperate stepmom trying to bond with me through a silly project. She'd mock the videos, call my stepmom cringe, but she never saw her as a threat. Just another stupid woman in my life. During filming, my stepmom would forget to turn Off her phone that was recording voice memos for content ideas. She'd schedule emergency reshoots whenever she noticed fresh bruises, making sure to get them on camera. While pretending to film my hands organizing drawer dividers. I had no idea that the whole time, she was just documenting everything. We were three weeks into our channel when Stella lost it. We saw a comment from a woman saying I had nice hands in our drawer organization video. The camera caught Stella attacking me with a kitchen knife, screaming about how I was just like her father, and how she'd make sure no woman ever looked at me again. When I tried to escape, she cornered me, saying she'd tell everyone I abused her if I ever left. That's when my stepmom walked back in, claiming she'd forgotten her lap.

Strangest family member everyone talks around but never talks about directly for context, I've always noticed how everyone gets super tense whenever Aunt Alana is mentioned or shows up at family gatherings. She's my dad's older sister, and there's like this unspoken rule that we don't talk about certain things around her or ask her certain questions. Growing up, I just thought maybe she was super sensitive or had depression or something, but the way everyone acts is way too strange for it to be just that. Whenever she visits, which is rare, maybe once every two to three years, my parents start acting so weird. Like a week before my mom deep clean the entire house, rearranges furniture, and hide certain family photos, my dad gets all quiet and starts drinking more than usual, and they both give me and my brother this weird lecture about being respectful and not bringing up the past, even though they never explain what past we're not supposed to bring up. The last time she visited before this weekend was at my cousin Edwin's graduation party three years ago. Everyone was having a good time until Uncle Rowland made some joke about how Edwin's girlfriend looked like someone from the family and the entire room went silent. My Aunt Alana just got up and left without saying anything. No one went after her. No one explained why that comment was so bad. Everyone just pretended nothing happened and kept eating cake. The mood Was completely ruined. So fast forward to this weekend. My parents were hosting a birthday dinner for my cousin Amber. She's 25, and somehow Aunt Alana agreed to come, which was already surprising because she usually skips these things. My mom spent three days cleaning and rearranging stuff. She even took down the family portrait from our living room wall, which was super weird because that photo has been there since I was like, 12. When Aunt Alana arrived, I swear the temperature in the room dropped like 10 degrees. Everyone was being polite, but so awkward. My dad kept refilling her wine glass like he was trying to get her drunk or something. And my mom kept starting random conversations whenever there was even a second of silence. My brother, he's 19, kept giving me these looks across the table like, WTF is happening? Because the tension was unbearable. Then during dessert, Amber started talking about how she's been using one of those DNA ancestry websites to make a family tree for her anthropology class. The moment she mentioned this, my dad literally choked on his drink, and my mom dropped a spoon so loudly, I jumped. Aunt Alana just sat there with this weird smile that didn't reach her eyes at all. Amber kept going, completely oblivious to the tension, about how she found some interesting patterns in our family history, how she wanted to interview everyone for her project. When she asked Aunt Alana if she'd be Willing to talk about the family history from her perspective, my Uncle William practically shouted about needing more ice for the drinks and dragged Amber to the kitchen. I was so confused and honestly kind of angry at this point because I felt like I was the only one not in on some huge family secret. So after dinner, when everyone was in the living room, I decided to follow Antilana when she went outside for some air. She was standing on our back porch just staring at the stars, and I awkwardly asked if she was enjoying the party. She gave me this look that was so sad, it actually made my stomach hurt. she asked me if I'd ever felt like I didn't belong in my own family. Before I could answer, she said something about how blood isn't always thicker than water and how some secrets should stay buried. I was about to ask her what she meant when my dad came running outside looking panicked. He tried to act casual, but I could tell he was freaking out that I was alone with Aunt Elena. He made some excuse about my mom needing help with the coffee and practically dragged me back inside. Later that night, after everyone left, I confronted my parents. I told them I was tired of being treated like a child and demanded to know what the big deal was with Aunt Alana. They tried to change the subject at first. But I wouldn't let it go. I said I was going to ask her directly next time if they wouldn't tell me. That's when my mom started crying

Your family ever bothered you over baby names? When my wife Emma and I found out we were having our first baby, we were over the moon. We spent weeks picking the perfect name. Oliver James. It felt right. Strong, but not too trendy. Classic, but not boring. We told everyone at my mom's birthday dinner when Emma was four months along. My. My older brother Jake just nodded and said, cool choice, while bouncing his two year old on his lap. His wife, Casey smiled and congratulated us. Everything seemed normal. Two months later, Jake called with big news. Casey was pregnant again. We were excited. Our kids would be close in age, maybe even best friends growing up. At Emma's baby shower, Casey was showing off her little bump to all the aunts. Someone asked if they'd picked names yet. Casey got this weird smile and said, well, if it's a boy, we're thinking Oliver James. The room went dead quiet. Emma's fork clattered onto her plate. I felt my face get hot. That's our name, I said, trying to keep my voice steady. We announced it months ago. Jake shrugged. It's a family name, bro. Grandpa Oliver, remember? We have just as much right to use it. That was complete bullshit. My grandpa went by Ali, and his middle name was Robert, not James. Jake was just making stuff up. Emma started crying right there at her own baby shower. My mom tried to smooth things over. Saying there could be two Olivers in the family. But Emma whispered to me that she couldn't handle having our special name stolen. That night. I was furious. I'd always been the little brother who got Jake's hand me downs, but this was our baby's name. Our one thing. Then I remembered something from college. My roommate had switched majors using some obscure policy buried in the student handbook that nobody ever read. Maybe there was something similar here. I spent three hours digging through old family documents my mom had given us for genealogy stuff. Birth certificates, marriage licenses, the works. And I found it. A handwritten family tree from 1987 that my great aunt had made. Right there in her careful cursive, it showed our great, great grandfather's full name. Oliver James Patterson. Not just Oliver, but Oliver James. The exact combination we'd chosen. I took a photo and sent it to Jake with a text. Found this in the family papers. Looks like Oliver James actually is a family name. Since Emma and I announced it first. And we're having our baby first. I think tradition says we get it. Jake tried to argue, but I could tell he was scrambling. He called me 20 minutes later, clearly having Googled family naming traditions. Fine, he said. But if Casey has a boy, we're using just Oliver. Whatever, I replied, as long as it's not Oliver James. Emma gave birth three weeks early. Our son came into the World as Oliver James. He was perfect. When Jake and Casey visited us in the hospital, Jake actually seemed happy for us. He held Oliver and said he looked just like our grandpa. Two months later, Casey had her baby, a healthy boy. They named him Oliver. At first, I felt bad. Maybe I'd been too aggressive about the whole thing. But then at the first family gathering with both babies, something amazing happened. My mom was holding both babies and got confused. Which Oliver is which? She asked, laughing. Casey looked annoyed. This is just Oliver, she said, gesturing to her son. That's Oliver James. From that day on, everyone called our son by his full name to avoid confusion. Oliver James became his identity. While Jake's son was just Oliver. Our boy got

My brother got me kicked out of the house so he could use my room as a game room, and now, years later, after discovering that I bought my own house, my parents are demanding that I give it to him. When I was younger, I lived with my mom, my stepdad, and my younger half brother. My brother was always their favourite because my mom hated seeing me, as I reminded her of my dad, whom she had cheated on, and for some reason she blamed me for it. I was often ignored and left out. For years I tried to ignore this and get by, but the situation became unbearable when I was about 14 years old. My brother was spoiled and always got what he wanted. He was really into video games, and over time he started complaining that the house didn't have enough space for him to have his own game room, something he had seen somewhere and now wanted. My parents then started hinting that I should leave the house so my brother could use my room as his game room. At first I thought they were joking, since they often told me to leave the house and that my presence there was useless, but then I realized they were serious. They began pressuring me to leave, saying that I was practically an adult and it was time to move on. I told them that I wasn't even old enough to have a job yet. Had nowhere to go and was far from being an adult. But as time passed, they decided it was time for me to go. And one day, I came home from school to find all my belongings thrown on the sidewalk. It was incredibly tough. I had to go from shelter to shelter until an angel appeared and adopted me. She was a police officer who lived near the shelter where I stayed the most, and we got to know each other. A few months later, she took me to live with her and eventually adopted me. Honestly, if it weren't for her, I don't know how I would have managed to move forward. Years went by, and I did my best to move on. I worked hard, studied, and saved enough money to buy my own house with my own business. I couldn't have done it without my adoptive mother for sure, as she financed my education and helped me pay to start my business. Now that things were going well for me, I also bought a house for her so she could get out of renting. However, when my biological family found out that I had bought a house and a house for my adoptive mother, apparently because the guy who sold me the house was a friend of my family, everything got worse again. If you want to watch the part 2, click on share and more!

Alcoholics. What made you stop drinking? When I was 16, my whole family died in a car accident. I was the only one who made it. One second, we were driving home from my sister's soccer game, laughing at something dumb. The next, I woke up in a hospital bed with a doctor standing over me, looking like he didn't want to be the one to say it. After that, I shut down. I had no close family, so they put me in foster care. The people who took me in barely acknowledged me. They made me sleep in the shed when I pissed them off. Some nights I went to bed hungry. I started sneaking out, getting strangers to buy me whatever cheap liquor I could get my hands on. By 18, I was homeless. My routine was simple. Wake up, go to work, buy booze, pass out, eat. I had no reason to stop. I didn't care if I woke up the next morning or not. Then one night, I was drinking outside a gas station when a cop pulled up. I kept my head down, waiting for him to tell me to move or arrest me. Instead, he leaned against his car and said, you even old enough for that? I shrugged. Yeah, basically. He looked at me for a second, then nodded toward his car. Get in. I figured, what the hell? Maybe a night in a cell would be better than this. But he didn't Take me to the station. He went inside the gas station and returned with a coffee and a bag of food. He handed them to me and said, eat. I stared at the bag. It had been a while since someone told me to eat like they actually cared. I didn't say much, but he got me to talk. I told him I had no one, no home, nothing. Listened, then told me to wait at the station until his shift ended. That night, he brought me to his place. Couch is yours, he said, tossing me a blanket. We'll figure things out in the morning. I don't know why, but I told him everything. My family, the drinking, the foster home. He just nodded like none of it surprised him. Then he told me he lost his wife in a car accident, too. Said he got it. He didn't try to fix me. He didn't lecture me. He just helped. Took me to get a new I D. Since mine was long gone. Helped me get a better job. Kept his fridge stocked and told me to eat whatever I wanted. If I disappeared for days on a Bender, he didn't yell. He just said, you done? When I stumbled back through the door one time, he found me passed out in my car and didn't say a word. Just opened the door, pulled me up and walked me inside. Sat me down at the kitchen table and put A plate of food in front of me. I could barely keep my eyes open. But I remember him saying, you keep doing this, you're gonna end up like the guys I scrape off the sidewalk at 3:00am. Laughed. Maybe that's the plan. He didn't laugh. Just shook his head and said, nah, not you. I didn't believe him, but something about the way he said it stuck with me. One day he came home and said, listen, I can get you into a program. Law enforcement. You just gotta sober up first. I wanted to say yes. I wanted to believe I could do it. But I couldn't. I told him no. Then one night, he didn't come home. The next morning, I saw the headline. Cop was shot in the line of duty. My stomach dropped. I ran to the hospital and pushed past the nurses until I found his room. He was unconscious, hooked up to machines. They said he'd live, but he'd need help. I told them I'd do it. For weeks.

Always dump lemon on all of my food. I grew up in this crazy household where literally any food was up for grabs. Like, you could make dinner, put leftovers in the fridge with your name on it, and wake up the next morning to find someone already ate half of it. My three brothers and my sister acted like our kitchen was some kind of free for all buffet. I'd buy groceries with my part time job money, make myself lunch for school, and come back to find it gone. Every single time. So I got creative. I started drowning everything I made in lemon juice. And I mean drowning it. Like, I'd squeeze an entire lemon on my pasta, my rice, my sandwiches, everything. At first it was gross, but honestly, I got used to it pretty quick. Actually started liking the taste. The best part? Nobody touched my food anymore. They'd open containers, see my lemon soaked leftovers, and immediately close them back up. Finally, my food was safe. Kept doing this even after I moved out for college and got my own apartment. Just became this weird habit, you know? Like some people put hot sauce on everything, I put lemon on everything. My roommates thought it was gross, but whatever, it was my food. Fast forward to last month. I went on this girl's trip to Miami with five of my friends from college. Split the Airbnb and activities evenly, but everyone paid for their Own food. Since Beth has celiac disease and Jenna's vegetarian and all that, we've been going out to dinner every night to these nice restaurants. I always ask the server for extra lemons. Usually got, like, four or five wedges. And squeeze them all over my food before eating. My friends were used to it by then. They'd roll their eyes and make jokes about how I was probably getting scurvy in reverse or something, but nobody really cared. Nurses, have you ever lied to save a patient from getting in trouble? I was an ER nurse on a military base. There was an accident during training. Accidents happen all day every day, but this one was a flight incident. Flight incidents are a big deal. People die and multi million dollar aircrafts are destroyed. This accident was no different. My patient was the pilot who ejected and survived. Unfortunately, everyone else on the flight did not. The accident was considered my patient's fault, so they brought the guy in. He walked in and was fine, but was wrecked with survivors guilt. I was the highest ranking nurse in the ER that day, and for that reason, the flight incident documentation was assigned to me. I was to perform the mandated blood draw to test the pilot for substances or alcohol. The room was somber. Deaths of people who were close to each other, like brothers, are easily the hardest thing to get through. The pilot's entire squadron, all his bosses, his bosses, bosses were there. I drew his blood. And it's a chain of custody, which means every person who touches the vials has to sign who they handed them off to. For legal purposes. It's all to verify that no one tampered or switched out a vial. I don't know why, but I drew excess blood. Probably because it was my habit to draw a vial or two extra in case a doctor wanted to add tests. So I wouldn't have to stick a patient with a needle twice. When I gathered my trash up, I put them in my pocket. I don't know why I did this. I usually would have just thrown them away, but I had them with me. When the pilot was discharged, his squadron went and got drunk together as they attempted to pull the pilot from an abyss of self blame. I suppose it is important when that's your job, to get past it so you can fly again. And I'm not going to judge anyone for how they managed to do that. It's got to be difficult going back to work with the same people, all of you, knowing you were piloting during an accident that killed other people. So they get a pass to go get blackout drunk. But not an hour after they left, the lab called me. There was a problem. The chain of custody. Blood draws needed to be drawn again. Someone had dropped the first ones on the floor and smashed it into a million pieces. Now he was at a bar getting drunk, and I had to call him and have him come in to get a new blood test. It would not be clean. He would have alcohol in his blood. But I still had to have him come in. Everyone understood the ramifications of what was happening. With alcohol in his blood sample that was taken for his flight incident, he would Be court martialed. There would be a trial, he would get charges, and he would do a lot of time in the slammer. His commanding officer came with him, and his expression was great. The pilot's fate was sealed. Unless he told the truth, that this was a redraw and that it happened well after the pilot was off duty. But that meant the flight incident report had no blood drawn, which would end this pilot's career. Walking the pilot into the room where I was drawing his blood was like walking the career to the gallows. The whole time I did the paperwork and drew the blood, I knew what I had to do.

How did a student almost give you a heart attack that year? I was lucky enough to have my daughter in my class when she reached eighth grade. But I also had a student named miles who just couldn't sit still. He constantly bugged the girls, always trying to flirt, and it usually ended with him getting slapped or sent to the office. I'd send him down so many times that the front desk basically expected him every day. Eventually, I moved him to the front of the room just so I could keep an eye on him. One day, he asked me if he could sit in the back. He didn't argue or act out. He just asked nicely. For some reason, I said yes. We were in the middle of an assignment, and the entire room was quiet. That's when I heard whispering from the back. I looked up and saw miles showing something to another student. At first glance, it looked exactly like a handgun. Froze for a second. I didn't know if I was seeing it right. Maybe it was a toy or a prop. But I couldn't tell from where I was sitting. And I knew I needed to get a better look without making a scene. I got up to help a student near the back and use that chance to look again. This time, I knew for sure it wasn't fake. It was real. I couldn't just leave the class either. I had to keep everyone safe. And most of all, I needed to get my daughter out of there. I texted the assistant principal in all caps, telling him exactly what I had seen. Then I waited. I kept glancing at my daughter, trying to keep it together, but minutes passed and no response came. I knew I had to do something. I quietly called over one of the students I trusted and handed her a note I had written. It said, ask me to go to the bathroom. Find the assistant principal, show him this tech, tell him to check his phone and leave the building right away. She nodded and left without a word. I went back to my desk and acted like nothing was wrong. Five long minutes later, someone knocked on the door. To outfox your ex in family court. My ex husband tried to prove I was an unfit mother by secretly recording our daughter, but he accidentally recorded himself being the terrible parent instead. When Derek and I divorced last year, he was furious that I got primary custody of our eight year old daughter, Emma. He immediately filed for a custody modification, claiming I was neglecting her and that she'd be better off living with him full time. For months leading up to our court date, Derek would show up unannounced for his visitation days with this smug look on his face, make these weird comments like, I hope you're treating Emma well when I'm not around and kids remember everything. You know, I thought he was just being his usual passive aggressive self until Emma started acting strange after spending weekends at his place. Come home asking weird questions like, mommy, do you think it's bad that you let me have cereal for breakfast? Or, daddy says good moms always pack healthy lunches. It was clear he was coaching her, trying to make me look bad. But I couldn't prove it, and Emma was too young to understand what was happening. I started getting paranoid about every parenting decision, wondering if somehow Derek was watching and judging everything I did. Three weeks before our court hearing, Emma came home from Derek's house with a small bruise on her arm. When I asked her about it, she said, daddy grabbed Me when I was being loud. But he said not to tell you because it would make you bad. My heart sank. I took pictures of the bruise and called my lawyer immediately. But when I asked Emma more questions, she seemed confused and scared, like she wasn't sure if she was supposed to tell me or not. The next week, Derek's lawyer filed a motion claiming I was coaching Emma to lie about him. They said I was the one manipulating her and that Derek had evidence of my parental alienation. I was terrified. How could he possibly have evidence when I wasn't doing anything wrong? The day before our hearing, Emma was playing with my phone while I was cooking dinner. Suddenly, she gasped and said, Mommy, why is there a video of me and daddy on your phone? I looked at the screen, and my blood ran cold. There was a video file that I definitely hadn't recorded. I opened it, and there was Derek filming Emma in his living room. But instead of showing me being a bad mom, the video showed something completely different. Derek was behind the camera coaching Emma on what to say. Remember, tell the judge that mommy doesn't help with your homework. His voice said clearly. And don't forget to mention that she lets you stay up too late on school nights. Emma, looking confused and tired, kept saying, but Mommy does help me with homework, and I don't stay up Late, Derek's voice got sharper. Emma, we practice this. You need to say exactly what I told you, or daddy might not get to see you anymore. Do you want that to happen? I watched in horror as my daughter started crying and Derek kept pushing her to repeat lies about me. The video was over 10 minutes long, and it showed him bribing her with candy and toys to say negative things about my parenting. But the most damning part came at the end. Emma had apparently been too loud while Derek was on a work call, and the video caught him grabbing her arm roughly and yanking her away from his desk. That's where the bruise came from. If you tell your mom about this, he said on the recording, she'll be so upset that she'll take you away from daddy forever. This is. It's our special secret, okay? I realised Derek had been secretly recording our daughter to try to build a case against me, but he'd accidentally captured his own coaching sessions instead. He must have somehow uploaded the wrong files to a shared cloud folder that synced to my phone. In court the next day, Derek's lawyer confidently presented their case about my supposed parental alienation. They claimed Derek

People who've been kidnapped, how did you survive? I was 12 when a man in a blue pickup truck pulled up next to me while I was walking home from school. He asked if I wanted to earn $20 helping him move boxes. My parents had always warned me about strangers, but $20 seems like a fortune to a kid who got $5 allowance. The moment I got in his truck, I knew I'd made a terrible mistake. He immediately locked the doors and started driving in the opposite direction of where he said we were going. When I asked where we were headed, he told me to shut up and sit still. He drove for what felt like hours to a small cabin in the woods. No neighbors, no cell towers, nothing but trees. He dragged me inside and tied me to a chair and what looked like a basement. The smell was awful, like something had died down there. For the first two days, he barely spoke to me except to bring stale bread and warm water. I cried constantly, begging him to let me go home. He just stared at me with these cold, empty eyes and said my parents probably hadn't even noticed I was gone yet. On the third day, he made a mistake. He left his phone on the table while he went upstairs to make himself lunch. I could hear him moving around in the kitchen above me. The rope around my wrists, Had loosened slightly from struggling, and I managed to work one hand free. I grabbed his phone and called the first number I could think of, my mom's work number that she'd made me memorize for emergencies. When she answered, I whispered as quietly as I could, mom, I've been kidnapped. I'm in a cabin somewhere. There are tall pine trees everywhere, and I can hear a train in the distance. Before I could say more, I heard his footsteps coming down the stairs. I quickly put the phone back and got my hand back in the rope just as he appeared. He looked at me suspiciously, but didn't seem to notice anything different. What I didn't know was that my mom had immediately called the police while staying on the line. They traced the call and started searching for cabins near train tracks in our area. Meanwhile, she kept calling his phone every few minutes, hoping I'd answer the next morning. He seemed agitated. He kept looking out the windows and pacing around the cabin. I realized later that police helicopters had been circling the area, getting closer to finding us. Started talking about moving me somewhere else, which terrified me. That afternoon, he went outside to load something into his truck. I heard him talking to someone on the phone, getting angry. While he was distracted, I noticed he'd left the basement door unlocked. This was my chance. Quietly climbed the stairs and saw him through the window. Still arguing on the phone by his truck. The front door was about 15 feet away. I knew I had to be smart about this. If I ran straight out, he'd see me immediately. Instead, I crawled on my hands and knees toward the back of the cabin. There was a small window near the floor that looks like it might be big enough for me to squeeze through. I managed to push it open and wiggle through, scraping my arms and legs on the frame. Once outside, I ran as fast as I could toward the sound of the train tracks. I figured if I could reach them, I might find help, or at least know which direction LED back to civilization. My legs felt like jelly from being tied up for days, but pure adrenaline kept me moving. After running for about 10 minutes, I heard dogs barking in the distance. Then I heard voices calling my name. It was the search and rescue team my mom had called in. I screamed as loud as I could and kept running toward the voices.

I even spent my entire monthly allowance on it. On the fateful day, I literally bathed myself in Cologne and brushed my teeth a million times. I even went ahead and watched tons of adult films to make sure I won't fumble by putting my tool in the wrong shed. I rushed over to her house, thinking I was as ready as I could be. However, there was one crucial aspect that I had glossed over. You see, we had only been dating for one month, and I hadn't confirmed who she was. It was 2022. We were in very progressive times. By that, I mean that I was about to be blindsided and traumatized. So anyway, I get to her house, and she takes me to her room. We began kissing and feeling up each other's body. The worst thing that happened when you swapped phones. My husband and I had this silly tradition where we'd swap phones for a day every month to keep our trust strong. It was his idea. He said couples who had nothing to hide shouldn't mind it. But last month's swap turned my entire life upside down. That morning started like any other swap day. I handed him my iPhone, he gave me his Android. The first few hours were normal. Boring work emails and random YouTube notifications. Then at lunch, a message popped up from someone named Nancy work. I can't wait to see you tonight, baby. Got that hotel room you like? My heart stopped. I click the chat history and nearly threw up. Hundreds of messages going back six months. Pictures I wish I could unsee. Hotel receipts, everything. But instead of confronting him immediately, something in me snapped. I remembered we had shared bank accounts, and he always handled the finances. I opened his banking app. Thank god he kept his password saved. That's when I discovered he'd been secretly funneling money into a private account. $40,000 of our savings, gone. Money we've been saving for a house. Money from my parents. I took screenshots of everything, then forwarded them to my email. But I wasn't done. Had eight more hours with his phone, and I was going to make them count. I logged into his Instagram and followed every single one of his co workers. Then I posted all the hotel receipts with Nancy's name circled in red caption guess who's been busy at the Holiday Inn next? I texted his mom the screenshots. She always bragged about raising a faithful man. Well, surprise then! I changed his email, password and security question just for fun. I also changed his Netflix profile name to Cheating Scumbag. The best part? I texted Nancy from his phone. My wife found out everything. Good luck explaining this to your husband. At six PM he came home with my phone acting completely normal. He even kissed my cheek like usual. I handed his phone back with the sweetest smile. How was your day, honey? Oh, pretty quiet.

What's the smartest way you've tested your daughter's boyfriend? I pretended I didn't speak English around him for six months and heard everything he said when he thought I couldn't understand. My daughter Emma started dating this guy Kyle last year. Nice looking kid, always super polite around me and my wife. Maybe too polite. He'd bring flowers every time he came over. Always offered to help with dishes, called me sir non stop. Something felt rehearsed about it. I was born in Brazil, but moved here when I was 10. No accent at all anymore, but my parents taught me to never lose my Portuguese. One night at dinner, Emma mentioned that Kyle was taking Spanish in college. I got this crazy idea. Next time he came over, I pretended I barely spoke English. Just smiled, nodded and spoke Portuguese with Emma translating that I'd had a stroke that affected my language centre. Emma was confused but played along. When I explained my plan in private, she thought I was being ridiculous, but agreed to help. The first few weeks, Kyle was exactly the same. Super respectful, patient with the language barrier. He even downloaded a translation app. By month, two cracks started showing. When Emma left to use the bathroom, he'd mutter things under his breath. This food is disgusting. How long is this dinner going to take? Once I heard him quietly mock my accent to himself. I pretended not to notice, just smiled and offered more Food. When Emma's birthday came around, Kyle showed up with an expensive bracelet. Later, I overheard him on the phone in our backyard. Yeah, I returned the cheap one.

The most satisfying time you've caught someone in a lie. I once knew a girl who claimed to have brain cancer. She was always using it to get sympathy from others while at the same time drinking and doing substances. She would go to a party, do substances, and drink all night, and the next day complain on Facebook that her chemo was making her really sick that day. She would always use the chemo excuse to mooch grass off of people as well. Basically, whenever she wanted a free bar tab or to get out of something her boyfriend wanted to do, brain cancer was her excuse. So one night I am at a Halloween party, and she is there using her fake brain cancer to get free things from guys. She is sitting in the corner smoking herb, crying about how hard it is to have this kind of cancer, how much the blast radiation makes her sick, and how each day is a struggle. Anyway, she gets up to walk to the bathroom and in her high, drunken state, trips and falls. Immediately, a bunch of people rush to her aid. Sorry. A side effect of the radiation is loss of balance. This was the last straw for me. I rushed over to her side and told her to stay on the ground. I have first responder training. You've just fallen, and your brain is in a very delicate state right now due to the blast radiation. Do I have your permission to help you? Yes, please help me. I feel funny. She lies, loving the attention she is getting from the entire party. I point to her boyfriend. Call 911. We need an ambulance here now. Explain to them that she is undergoing blast radiation for brain cancer. She has taken a hard fall and could have suffered a head injury. At this point, she starts to panic. Why are you calling 911? Don't do that. Here, let me call my personal doctor instead. Don't call 911! I calmly tell her boyfriend and the group of bystanders that she really should go to the ER. Of course, he insists. Long story short, the paramedics show up, we tell them what's going on, and they take her to the hospital in the ambulance. We all get rides to the hospital, and because we are such a large group, are asked to sit in the waiting room. When the nurse finally comes out to the waiting room after her MRI to let us know that she's fine, her boyfriend mentions the brain cancer. The nurse, of course, is completely confused by this question. The boyfriend prods for more info from the nurse and basically finds out in front of the entire group that she does not have brain cancer. Everyone wtfs and leaves, including her Bf

Child say in court that saved someone's life. My five year old daughter's neighbor Carlos was a 19 year old who worked three jobs to support his younger siblings. Every morning, he'd wave to Lily on his way to work, and she'd run to the fence to show him her drawings. Lily called him her best grown up friend. One Saturday morning, police cars surrounded Carlos's house. There had been a break in six blocks away, and someone gave them Carlos's name as a suspect. The elderly victim, Missus Patterson, was in intensive care, fighting for her life after being brutally attacked during the robbery. The evidence seemed overwhelming. Carlos match the description. Young Hispanic male, about 6 feet tall. He'd been doing odd jobs in that neighborhood. Most damning, they found Missus Patterson's stolen jewelry in his work truck. Though Carlos swore someone planted it there. Carlos was arrested and charged with aggravated robbery and attempted murder. His family couldn't afford a good lawyer. The prosecution painted him as a dangerous criminal targeting vulnerable elderly victims. He was looking at 25 years to life for a crime I was certain he didn't commit. I knew Carlos was innocent. I'd seen him that Saturday morning working in our shared garden. But the timeline was tight. That's when I remembered. Lily had been playing in our backyard that entire morning, chattering non stop to Carlos while he worked. She'd been helping him plant tomatoes and asking him a million questions. Called Carlos's lawyer about Lily's potential testimony. He was skeptical. Child witnesses are unreliable, but I insisted we try. We spent hours preparing Lily, explaining she needed to tell the truth about that Saturday morning when Carlos was planting vegetables. The prosecution had presented their case with confidence, DNA evidence, witness descriptions, and stolen jewelry. When the defense called Lily to the stand, the courtroom went silent. As this tiny girl walked up to the witness box, the judge adjusted the microphone down to her level. Lily, the lawyer began gently, do you remember Saturday morning when Carlos was working in your garden? She nodded seriously. We were planting the tomato babies. She said clearly. Carlos was very careful with them because baby plants can die if you're not gentle. What else do you remember? She brightened. Carlos taught me about bugs, and he showed me how his hands were all dirty from the special plant food. And he said he couldn't touch anything clean until we wash them. The lawyer asked, did Carlos wash his hands that morning? Oh, yes, she said proudly. We wash them together at the garden faucet with the special soap. Carlos said dirty hands make everything dirty, so we scrubbed until they were super clean. But then Lily added something that changed everything. And Carlos was very sad about his work gloves. The lawyer asked her to explain.

Best school life hack. My high school teacher, Mr. Jordan, had a rule that rewarded the laziest people in class. His rule was all members of a group project will receive the same grade no matter what. He had beady eyes, a long white beard, and refused to wear anything other than expensive suits to work. Whenever anyone complained about his outdated rule, he'd tell us that this was what the real world was like, and if we weren't ready for something this simple, we'd probably end up homeless anyway. Like, what the F. Anyway, I thought it wouldn't affect me, since me and my friends refused to let anyone take the heavier load of work. Until one day when he announced the forbidden words no student ever wants to hear. Assigned group projects go. I crossed my fingers and hoped for the best. But I guess I didn't cross my fingers hard enough, because I ended up being assigned with the wasters of our class. You know, the ones constantly smelling like the devil's lettuce. Skipped class at least once a day. Thought it was cool to have a GPA of 1.5. It's like I could see the future, because I instantly knew that working with them was a death sentence. End of class, I ran up to Mr. Jordan, practically begging him to adjust the equal grades policy. Just this once. He lifted his single index finger that was stained with yellow from his chain smoking habit. No, No, no, he said slowly. Like I said, no exceptions. If you don't like it, then you can leave. I had to stop myself from rolling my eyes like, why do teachers always say that? I literally don't have a choice whether I can leave or not. But thanks anyway. I was determined for that old effort to change his policy. So much so that I began to document everything. The first week I scheduled a team meeting. At first no one in the group chat replied to me, so I started spamming it with Bitmoji stickers and refused to stop until everyone replied. When the day came, Wednesday at 7 p. M, no one showed up. The next morning everyone texted in their excuses, but it was too late. I already had my screenshot. Mwah ha ha! And in our Google document, I was the only one making any contributions. Heck, none of those slackers even put their effing name on it. The worst part is, is that they knew they were doing Jack shit. Sometimes they text in the group and say things like every group needs a beach. Guess we found ours. Or it's so hot how submissive you are. Thanks, beach! But every time I just smiled because I knew after the project was over, their lives would never be the same again. It was around this time that I did the most insane thing known to mankind. I read the student handbook after dozens of Paper cuts and almost falling asleep. I finally found it. Right there on page 39. District Educational Code Section 4.7. Individual assessment must be available when documented disparity exceeds 40%. I let out a sigh of relief. Everything I had done up to this point would be used for good. All I had to do was prove that I did over 40% of the group project. Over the next few days, I poured everything into making sure the group project was perfect. I even started replying to their group chat messages about how their GPS would be completely messed up if it wasn't for me. How I was saving them from flunking out. Then the due date finally came. I walked into that classroom like a soldier on a battlefield, fully equipped with armor. Mr. Jordan wanted us to present it in front of the class, old school. When we did, the wasters didn't even try to hide the fact that they were reading off the board. By the end, we all got A's. But their Celebration was cut short. Mister Jordan, it's clear I did much more work than them. They don't deserve that grade. No, no, no! He interrupted. All group members in a project will receive the same grade no matter what. I smirked and put up another.

What's the most disturbing school announcement your school has ever made? I was in the middle of texting my friends the road work ahead Vine during math class when the principal coughed over the school intercom, the tell tale sign that he was about to make an announcement. Attention all students and staff. No one has to leave their classrooms. Everyone must remain seated until further notice. This is for your safety as much as ours. Usually no one gave an F what the teacher said, but now it was so quiet that you could hear a pin drop. Even Mrs. Peterson stopped writing on the board mid sentence. We heard ambulances outside and she told us to sit in our seats. We're all glancing at each other around the room, wide eyed and curious. Nobody said anything, but we were all thinking the same thing. One of the teachers had died. The red and blue lights flashed across the walls and we heard screams from the other grades echoing throughout the building. Mrs. Peterson told us that it wasn't a big deal and we should all be focusing on our studies. But we could barely get the words out from how hard she was hyperventilating, so much so that she didn't even care. As we all started to take our phones out and text our theories into the Snapchat group chat about what was going down. Then we heard it. Footsteps running past our door. Heavy ones. Multiple sets. I couldn't help myself. I had to look. I crept to the door and peeked through the window. Two paramedics were sprinting down the hall, pushing a wheeled stretcher, the kind you see on medical shows when someone's heart stops. Get away from the door, Eve. Missus Peterson whispered, voice shaking. She was scared, too. I sat down and immediately texted everyone what I had seen. people's bitmojis were popping up faster than a whack a mole game. Maybe someone finally took out Mr. Jordan, the creepy history teacher. Now someone definitely just had an allergic reaction. Peanut allergies go crazy. Another one said that maybe someone had taken too much fent. Mrs. Peterson tried to continue the lesson. Something about the Revolutionary War, but nobody was listening. Could we care about some battle from 200 years ago when someone might be dying down the hall right now? Finally, there was a knock at the door. It was the principal standing beside a police officer. Eve O'Brien, the principal announced. My heart dropped. That was me. Can you come with us, please? Bring your things. I silently got up and followed, not knowing what the f was going on. In the hallway, I could see the paramedics near the gym. One was sitting on the floor filling out paperwork. The

Dream workers. What's the most disturbing thing you've ever seen? I work at Smash Zone downtown, and let me tell you, we get all kinds of weirdos. People come in to break stuff when they're pissed about divorces, job losses, whatever. But this one guy from last month still gives me chills. It was a Tuesday afternoon, super slow. This dude walks in wearing a wrinkled button up shirt and jeans that looked like he'd slept in them. He's got these balloons tied around his wrist. Cheap kind from dollar stores. Red, blue, yellow. Real cheerful looking. Hey there, he says with this big smile. I'd like your basic package, please. I'm thinking, okay, birthday boy wants to blow off some steam. Happens all the time. But then I noticed his hands are shaking as he fills out the waiver. Not nervous, shaking like he'd been drinking too much coffee for three days straight. Actually, he says, looking up from the paperwork, can I bring my own stuff to smash? I've got some personal items. We allow it sometimes if it's safe. He pulls out this beat up shoebox from a backpack. Inside there's random junk. An old digital clock with a cracked screen, a Superman lunch box that's all dented up, and maybe six or seven VHS tapes. Nothing dangerous, he says, reading my face. Just some old memories I need to get rid of. I check everything over. No glass, no chemicals, nothing sharp. Just weird old stuff. That smelled like basement storage. Can I get the room with the brick wall? He asks. The one that echoes really good? That's room three. Most people want the padded rooms because they're quieter, but whatever. I suit him up in safety gear and show him in. Here's where it got freaky. I always watch through the window for safety reasons. Usually people go nuts immediately. Screaming, crying, throwing stuff around like maniacs. This guy, dead silent. He picks up the alarm clock first, holds it like it weighs 50 pounds. Then he starts whispering to it. I can't hear what he's saying through the glass, but his lips are moving the whole time. After maybe two minutes of this, he raises it over his head and smashes it against the brick wall. Same thing with the lunch box. Whispers to it, then destroys it with the baseball bat. We provide the V H S. Tapes. He crushes one by one under his boot, still talking to each one before he destroys it. The whole thing takes him maybe 20 minutes. I'm starting to think he's done when he reaches into the box one more time. He pulls out a piece of paper. Even from the window, I can tell it's a kid's drawing. You know how they look with those thick crayon lines and stick figures. He unfolds it real careful and just stares at it for 10 solid minutes. This guy stands there holding the straw, not moving. Barely breathing, I'm starting to wonder if I should check on him when he suddenly folds it back up, sets it on the little table in the middle of the room, and walks out. All done, he says, like nothing happened, pays in cash, tips me 20 bucks, and leaves with those stupid balloons still tied to his wrist. Go in to clean up the room, and it's trashed. Bits of plastic and metal everywhere. But that drawing is sitting perfectly folded on the table, untouched. I almost threw it away, but something felt wrong about it, so I stuck it in our lost and found box instead. Three hours later, two cops show up.

My obsessive cousin keeps trying to copy me, so I lied about being pregnant. When I was younger, I used to do everything with my cousin. We styled our hair the same, like the same singers, and try to match outfits with each other. We were always known as being very close in the family. However, as we grew up, she always tried to outdo me and say how much better she was than me, which I did find odd. I ended up always letting it slide because my mom would always say that we were better off than she was, and I really just wanted to hang out with her, but at the end of the day, it was never enough. Last year, my fiance proposed to me, and I was overjoyed and told my family. I also told my cousin and her boyfriend when they came over for Thanksgiving, and she seemed kind of upset. It seemed like she was bothered that I even told her, but she left before I could ask her about it. I dismissed it, thinking she was having a rough day. However, three weeks later, I discovered my cousin was engaged and trying to plan it as soon as possible. I thought it was just a coincidence that we both got engaged around the same time, and I was really happy for her. Eventually, she gave up trying to rush her wedding, and I didn't hear from her for a while. Recently, my Mom told me the day she wanted to get married, her date was the exact same day my fiance and I decided on. I was upset at this point and asked her about why she was acting strange about the wedding and choosing the same date as me. She only replied by saying it was just a coincidence and that I should stop being jealous that I didn't have what she had. After hearing that, I was surprised and offended. Did she really think I was jealous? I tried to tell my family about how strange and unfair it was that she got engaged and wanted to get married on the same day as me, but they all told me I was overreacting. I was so upset no one believed me that I ended up taking things into my own hands and wanted to catch her in the act. So I told my cousin I was pregnant just to see what she would do. And wouldn't you know it. Two weeks later, she also announced she was pregnant. I tried to tell my family what had happened and how suspicious it was, but they still didn't believe me. Ultimately, I wanted to prove a point and would do anything to make sure they knew I was right. You can now check part 2 by pressing share, then more!

My ex told me I was too much to be loved. My husband thinks I'm perfect. My ex used to say I was too much, too emotional, too loud, and too sensitive. I cry at movie trailers. I'd laugh too loud at his jokes. I'd hug my friends too tight at parties. And every time he'd flinch. Every time, he'd sigh and say, god, can you just tone it down for once? I started shrinking myself. Stopped laughing out loud, stopped dreaming out loud, stopped being out loud. It felt like he just didn't want me to exist at all. I still remember the night it hit me. We were at a dinner party, and he told a story about me to everyone. He exaggerated everything and mocked my movements like I was a MIME. And everyone laughed. I laughed, too, because that's what you do when you're scared someone you love is embarrassed by you. Afterward, I sat outside the coffee shop, wishing I could press a button and disappear. I was on the phone, venting to my best friend about what had just happened. She ended our call by saying, he might have a point, though. I started crying. And that's when a stranger, a guy sitting at the table next to mine. Slid a napkin across my table. On it, he'd scribbled, the right person won't need you to shrink. Here's my number if you ever need someone to be yourself with. I almost threw it away. Almost convinced myself it wasn't meant for me. But something told me to tuck it into my purse. That stranger became my best friend. And eventually my husband. It was an instant. It wasn't fireworks. It was years of moments together. Him clapping the loudest when I got excited. Him laughing until he cried when I accidentally knocked a whole tray of cupcakes onto the floor. Him telling me, god, I love how you feel. Everything. Last week, I asked him, just joking, don't you ever wish I was a little less much? He kissed my forehead and said, I didn't marry you in spite of your too much. I married you because of it. Turns out I was never too much. I was just too much for the wrong people. Now I'm everything for someone who wouldn't want me any other way.

A banned from an all you can eat buffet. So I made sure the owner never ate in peace again. You ever get kicked out of somewhere for doing exactly what you were told you could do? Yeah, me too. It happened at this grimy little place called Big Benny's. All you can eat buffet. 1499. No time limit, no small print. Just pay, eat, repeat. Or so I thought. Now I'm not some competitive eater or 600 pound menace with bib and back problems. I'm just a guy with an appetite and a grudge against portion control. I hadn't eaten in 24 hours. Why? Because I prepared for this. Fasting, hydrating, mentally visualizing the tray of ribs like it was the Olympic podium. You know, normal stuff. First plate, fried chicken, Mac and cheese, two rolls. Nothing crazy. I'm eating into it. Second plate, more carbs. Potatoes, lasagna, garlic bread. Third, I start seeing staff eyeing me like I'm stealing food from their children. One of the servers actually slowed down as she walked past like I was a suspicious dog growling near her purse. By the fifth plate, I swear the manager was hiding behind the soda machine like I was gonna bite him. Play seven. That's when it got interesting. I went full throttle. Barbecue ribs stacked like Lincoln Logs, a pile of meatballs, three chicken thighs and six brownies. I definitely didn't take from the kids section. I said down, fork in hand. When the manager Finally slithered over with two of his most underpaid teenage minions flanking him like henchmen from a movie. No one finishes. He goes, sir, we're going to have to ask you to leave. You've exceeded reasonable consumption. Excuse me. What? Is there a rule on how much I can eat? I asked. There isn't. But, you know, I actually don't know. Benny, I know you have a sign up front in Comic Sans that says all you can eat. It does not say all. We feel emotionally comfortable watching you eat. So I stood up, and you know what I did? I went back for plate No.. 8. He called the cops. I wish I was kidding. Imagine being mid bite into a drumstick, sauce on your chin, when two actual police officers walk in like you're a suspect in a felony mashed potato incident. They looked at me, then at Benny, then back at me. One of them goes, what exactly did he do? He won't stop eating. There was this long pause, the kind that only happens when someone says something so stupid. Has to be processed in layers. The officer turned to me, look, man, could you just go? He looked embarrassed for the manager. I asked if I could at least finish my plate. Then he said, no. Of course he did. I was dangerous, a biological threat to his bottom line. So I was escorted out of Big Benny's all you can eat buffet. Like I robbed the place at Gravy Point, and as I walked out then he had the nerve to say, you're banned for life loudly in front of other customers. Like I was going to miss the place. Now, most people would move on, chalk it up to a ridiculous story to tell at parties, but I don't.

Spiked my drink at a party, so I made him terrified of liquids. You know that one guy at every party? The one who thinks he's God's gift to alcohol and women? The guy who says things like, I mix better than I date, and if you can't handle a little fun, go home? Yeah, that guy. For me, that guy had a name. Mason. Mason was the kind of guy who wore sunglasses indoors and took shirtless mirror pics like it was a civic duty. He thought spiking people's drinks was hilarious. Just a little joke, bro, he'd say. Like slipping something into someone's drink was on par with drawing a mustache on a passed out friend. Spoiler alert. It's I found out the hard way. It was during our friend Bailey's New Year's party. Good people, decent music, enough food to soak up the bad decisions. I grabbed a drink off the kitchen island. Non alcoholic cause I was the designated driver. Took a few. It tasted a little weird. Like if regret had a flavor. I figured maybe the soda was flat. Ten minutes later, the room started spinning like it was trying to detach from earth. I barely made it to the bathroom before my legs went full Jello. My heart was racing, skin crawling, and I was suddenly having a deep, personal conversation with the floor tiles. Bailey found me an hour later, curled up like a shrimp in her tub. She called an ambulance. Thank God! Turns out Mason had decided to spy suck the party by adding something to my drink. Something prescription based. Something not meant for conscious humans. He thought it was funny. Dude, you should have seen your face, he said, laughing when I confronted him. Relax, I gave you the light stuff. Ah, yes, just a sprinkle of involuntary coma. How festive. I wanted to punch him, but I'm not stupid. People forget bruises, but they don't forget fear. Especially the kind that seeps in drop by drop. So I made a decision. Mason was going to become terrified of liquids. All of them. The plan took finesse. I couldn't just scream Benge! And run at him with a water balloon. This had to feel like karma was slowly dripping down his neck. And it started with coffee. I knew Mason's routine. Every morning, same cafe, same order. Iced triple espresso with oat milk, vanilla, two pumps of ego. So I applied for a job at that cafe. Not because I needed it, but because revenge requires commitment. After three weeks of being the overly eager new guy, I got barista duty. When Mason walked in, I greeted him with my best you probably don't remember drugging me smile. He didn't recognize me. Perfect. I made his drink. Nothing in it yet, but after handing it to him, I leaned over and said, we've had a few complaints about mold in the oatmeal.

The worst thing that happened when you swapped phones. My husband and I had this silly tradition where we'd swap phones for a day every month to keep our trust strong. It was his idea. He said couples who had nothing to hide shouldn't mind it. But last month, swap turned my entire life upside down. That morning started like any other swap day. I handed him my iPhone, he gave me his Android. The first few hours were normal. Just boring work emails and random YouTube notifications. Then at lunch, a message popped up from someone named Nancy work. I can't wait to see you tonight, baby. Got that hotel room you like? My heart stopped. I click the chat history and nearly threw up. Hundreds of messages going back six months. Pictures I wish I could unsee. Hotel receipts, everything. But instead of confronting him immediately, something in me snapped. I remembered we had shared bank accounts, and he always handled the finances. I opened his banking app. Thank god he kept his password saved. That's when I discovered he'd been secretly funneling money into a private account. $40,000 of our savings, gone. Money we've been saving for a house. Money from my parents. I took screenshots of everything, then forwarded them to my email. But I wasn't done. Had eight more hours with his phone, and I was going to make them count. I logged into his Instagram and followed every single one of his co workers. Then I posted all the hotel receipts with Nancy's name circled in red caption guess who's been busy at the Holiday Inn? Next, I texted his mom the screenshots. She always bragged about raising a faithful man. Well, surprise! Then I changed his email, password, and security question just for fun. I also changed his Netflix profile name to Cheating Scumbag. The best part? I texted Nancy from his phone. My wife found out everything. Good luck explaining this to your husband. At six PM he came home with my phone, acting completely normal. He even kissed my cheek like usual. I handed his phone back with the sweetest smile. How was your day, honey? Oh, pretty quiet.
