That one time that you had to turn to the dark side. One day, my daughter came back from school and ran into my arms like she was scared. I could feel her shaking, so I took her inside and made some French toast, which was her favorite food. I thought she just had a really bad day and missed being at home, but I couldn't have been more wrong. When she calmed down, she told me, Mommy, something happened today, and I think I'm supposed to tell you about it. An uneasy knot formed itself in my heart when she told me that the school counselor had called her into his office for a special game. He handed my daughter a stuffed unicorn and told her that this new game was very popular with the children, which made my daughter excited and eager to learn. Then the counselor made her point the unicorn between his legs and push on it repeatedly. My daughter told me how he made weird faces at times and then closed his eyes and leaned back. Towards the end, I was so horrified and felt a wave of nausea rush through my body, so I had to go to the bathroom and throw up. What kind of sick person would make a seven year old girl do this kind of thing? Not to mention he worked at a school and it was me who willfully sent my daughter near his vicinity. I kept bouncing between Blaming myself and wanting to burn the entire world. My husband was no longer with us, so it was up to me to stand up for my daughter. I don't know what made me approach the school administration before the police, but that's exactly what I did. And the school administration laughed at me, saying that my daughter was clearly playing a prank. They said they had heard other students make similar jokes about the school counselor and said that parents should teach their kids not to lie. But by the time I made it to the police station, the school had already called them and explained the situation. They thought I was a crazy mother who was trying to give merit to my daughter's filthy lie. I had looked straight into my daughter's eyes when she told me the story, so I knew she was telling the truth. But no one wanted to believe me, and I felt like I was in a nightmare. This is when I remembered something important and ran back home to open my jewelry safe. Inside there was a note that I hadn't looked at for a long time. See, although I was currently a doctor, I had been a very inexperienced nurse at one point. And one time, a very stern looking man with a lot of face tattoos walked into our hospital with a bullet wound. No other nurse wanted to treat him since he looked so scary, so they sent me I convinced myself that everyone deserves treatment and cleaned his wounds with the utmost concentration. I even engaged him in conversation and joked about how he should stay away from bullets in the future. When it was all over, the guy thanked me and handed me a note with his phone number on it. Said, if you ever need someone taken care of, I won't ask for any payment. I typed in that phone number and to my surprise, it actually connected. I told him who I was and he said, I remember you.

Realize you needed to quit your addiction. But I almost called someone who trusted me with their life. I'm a heart surgeon and in the early stages of my addiction, I promised myself I'd never operate high. I told myself I was in control and I could stop at any time. As you can guess, it didn't take long for me to show up to a projected 17 hour surgery absolutely smacked. I'd operated while intoxicated before this. I was used to that, but this was a whole different level of smack. I was on like four different substances. I still don't know what made me think this was okay. I think I was just so broken in every other area of my life that at the time, and I know this sounds horrible, I didn't even care if I accidentally cold the 58 year old father of three, whose children trusted me with his life. His family was in the waiting room praying, and I felt absolutely nothing looking at them. The surgery started around 7 a m. And by 9:30, I was already jonesing for another hit. I excused myself for a bathroom break and shot up in the stall. My hands stopped shaking and I went back in. Sarah, my head nurse who'd worked with me for 10 years, kept giving me these looks. During the pre op briefing. She'd asked if I was okay and mentioned I seemed off. I saw her exchange glances with the Anesthesiologist and my paranoia went through the roof. By 1 p m, I'd taken three more bathroom breaks to top off. Each time I came back, Sarah documented something in her notes. I dropped an instrument and blamed it on new gloves, but I could tell nobody was buying it. She suggested calling Doctor Chan to take over and I snapped at her, accusing her of undermining my authority. The whole OR went silent after that. Around three PM, I realized I was running low on supplies. I'd only brought enough for what I thought would get me through, but I've been using more than usual because of the stress. I started rushing through the procedure, trying to turn a 17 hour hour operation into 10. I skipped double checking suture lines and my hands were visibly shaking. While working on this man's heart. The anesthesiologist asked why I was rushing and I barked at him to mind his own job. I made an incision too deep and to compensate while Sarah quietly documented everything. The whole team was on edge and I'd created this hostile environment where everyone was afraid to speak up even though they knew something was seriously wrong. By five PM, I was in full withdrawal mode. 10 hours in and I'd burned through everything I had on me. My hands were trembling so bad I could barely hold the instruments. I was sweating through my scrubs, and my vision was getting blurry. All I could Think about was getting home to my stash. This man's chest was cracked open in front of me, and all I cared about was getting high. I started closing him up as fast as possible, just trying to get out of there. That's when everything went to hell. The patient started hemorrhaging badly during the chest closure. His blood pressure crashed, and alarms started screaming. The OR erupted into controlled chaos as everyone scrambled to save him, while I just stood there frozen for a second. I managed to find the bleeder, but the damage was already done. He needed a mask.

People who were kicked out of their homes. What happened? I taught my cousins a language that changed our lives forever. You see, my family had this rule about women and silence. A woman's voice was considered poison. After her 16th birthday, the silence ceremony happened at midnight. Your father holds you down while your mother sews a red thread across your lips. Not literally, but you wore that thread on your wrist as a reminder. Break the rule once, they'll lock you in the laundry room without food. Break it twice, they'll pull a tooth. Nobody broke it three times. Women's silence was like a currency. Whichever man had the quietest house was the most praised in society. At family gatherings, my uncles would compete like kids showing off baseball cards. Mira hasn't made a sound since January, Uncle Dev would boast, spreading his fingers in response. Uncle Raj would lean back, smirking. That's nothing. Priya is going on two years. When the doctor asked her a question at her check up, she just pointed at me to answer. It actually sounds crazy saying it out loud, but for so long, this is just the way things were. And I myself was the loudest person I knew. I couldn't even get through a conversation without laughing at something the other person said, even if it wasn't meant to be funny. I loved singing lyrics out loud and making weird sounds with my friends. So I knew if I didn't Find an answer soon, then my life would be over. But I wanted the problem to go away by itself. And one day, it did. I was sitting in seventh grade when Miss Brown told us that we needed to take a foreign language. My ears perked up because ASL, American Sign Language, counted. You see, the whole time, me and my family were in the USA. Because it wasn't until you turned 16 and made the vow of silence before you were sent back to the motherland. And there you were forced to settle down and have kids. So three times a week, I sat in Mister Brown's classroom learning to speak with my hands. Adrenaline pumped through my veins. If she so much as texted my parents about my choice of language, they'd find out what I was up to, and my life would be over. I even didn't know what I was going to do with the lessons because no one around me spoke the language. But then came Diwali dinner. All our relatives flew in from in the motherland to eat at our house. It was supposed to be the happiest time of the year. But during the meal, I noticed Priya sitting by herself at the end of the table. There were tears silently streaming down her face, and she was unable to tell anyone why. She was 17. A year into her silence, when no one was looking, I handed her a glass of Water. With a note in my hand. Meet me by the garden shed. Bring your sister. I told everyone that I noticed her sorry was wrinkled and I was going to teach her how to fold it properly in the shed. That's how it started. Every family gathering. While the men watched cricket and the silenced women served food, me and the younger girls would cluster together, all desperate to avoid our fate. I taught them letters first, then words. Then we had whole conversations flowing between our fingers. We got creative with practice locations, signing while washing dishes, our hands hidden in soapy water. We developed our own secret gesture. A flick of the wrist meant he's coming. A thumb brush meant save this conversation for later. By the time I turned 15, we had a full network. 12 girls between the ages of 9 and 15, all fluent in a language our fathers and brother

You realize your parents shouldn't have had kids. I was 15 when I found out. My parents had a group chat where they talked about how much they regretted having me. My mom left her phone on the kitchen counter while she was in the shower. The screen lit up with a text from my dad that said, Jake's being dramatic again. I wasn't trying to snoop, but I saw my name, so I looked. Big mistake. It was a group chat with my mom, dad, and my Aunt Diane. I scrolled up and my stomach dropped. Jake failed another math test. Why can't he be more like Tommy? That was from three days ago. Tommy's my little brother. He's 12 and basically perfect at everything. I kept scrolling. Honestly regret not stopping after Tommy. Jake's just exhausting. That was my mom from last week. My dad had written back, at least Tommy appreciates what we do for him. Jake just complains. There were months of messages like this. Calling me lazy, saying I was a waste of money. One message from my aunt said, maybe boarding school, and my mom replied, we've thought about it. I sat there staring at that phone for like 20 minutes. Everything suddenly made sense. Why they forgot to pick me up from soccer practice, but never missed Tommy's games. Why my birthday dinner was always at some random place, but Tommy got parties at his favourite restaurant. Last Christmas, I got a twenty Dollar gift card to Target. Tommy got a PlayStation 5 and 3 games. When I asked about it, my mom said, we spent the same amount. You're just being ungrateful. I took screenshots of everything before my mom got out of the shower. When she came downstairs, I was sitting at the table eating cereal like nothing happened. Morning, honey, she said, grabbing her phone. Morning, I said. Back that night at dinner, they were asking Tommy about his day and completely ignored me. Nothing new there. But now I knew why. My dad asked Tommy, how was band practice? Tommy plays trumpet and his first chair or whatever. Then my mom turned to me. Jake, did you finish your homework? Most of it, I said. She rolled her eyes. Most of it isn't good enough. Tommy always finishes his. I wanted to scream. Instead, I just said, I'll finish it after dinner. Three weeks later, I overheard them talking in their bedroom. I was walking past to use the bathroom and heard my name. Jake's grades are getting worse. Maybe we should just let him figure it out himself, my dad said. I'm tired of caring more about his future than he does, my mom replied. That's when I realized they'd already given up on me. They were just waiting for me to turn 18 so they could stop pretending. I started keeping a journal of every time they treated Tommy different. Every forgotten pickup. Every time they bought Him something and told me, maybe next time. Every family photo where they put him in the middle and me off to the side. The worst part? Tommy had no idea. He genuinely thought our parents loved us equally. Sometimes he'd even stick up for me when they were being obvious about it. Two months ago, my mom's sister came to visit. She was the one from the group chat. At dinner, she made some comment about how well Tommy was doing in school. And Jake's trying his best, too, Tommy said, looking at me. My aunt laughed. Sure he is. My mom shot her a look, but didn't say anything to defend me. That night, I showed Tommy the screenshots. He cried. Actually cried. He said he never noticed how different they treated us and felt horrible. I'm going to talk to them, he said. Don't, I told him. Won't change anything. At least now we both know. Three days later, Tommy came to my room with his report card. All A's, like always. I'm not showing them this, he said. Why not? They'll be proud. Because they should be proud of you, too. You got two b's, and that's awesome. I got two b's and three C's, actually. But Tommy was trying to be nice. Crazy part is, my parents still have no idea I know about the group chat. They keep acting like everything's normal. Well, normal for them, which means treating Tommy like their golden child. And me like some random kid they got stuck with.

Child say in court that saved someone's life. My five year old daughter's neighbor Carlos was a 19 year old who worked three jobs to support his younger siblings. Every morning he'd wave to Lily on his way to work, and she'd run to the fence to show him her drawings. Lily called him her best grown up friend. One Saturday morning, police cars surrounded Carlos's house. There had been a break in six blocks away. And someone gave them Carlos's name as a suspect. The elderly victim, Missus Patterson, was in intensive care, fighting for her life after being brutally attacked during the robbery. The evidence seemed overwhelming. Carlos match the description. Young Hispanic male, about 6 feet tall. He'd been doing odd jobs in that neighborhood. Most damming, they found Missus Patterson's stolen jewelry in his work truck. Though Carlos swore someone planted it there. Carlos was arrested and charged with aggravated robbery and attempted murder. His family couldn't afford a good lawyer. The prosecution painted him as a dangerous criminal targeting vulnerable elderly victims. He was looking at 25 years to life for a crime I was certain he didn't commit. I knew Carlos was innocent. I'd seen him that Saturday morning working in our shared garden. But the timeline was tight. That's when I remembered. Lily had been playing in our backyard that entire morning, chattering non stop to Carlos while he worked. She'd been helping him plant tomatoes and asking him a million questions. Called Carlos's lawyer about Lily's potential testimony. He was skeptical. Child witnesses are unreliable, but I insisted we try. We spent hours preparing Lily, explaining she needed to tell the truth about that Saturday morning when Carlos was planting vegetables. The prosecution had presented their case with confidence, DNA evidence, witness descriptions, and stolen jewelry. When the defense called Lily to the stand, the courtroom went silent. As this tiny girl walked up to the witness box, the judge adjusted the microphone down to her level. Lily, the lawyer began gently, do you remember Saturday morning when Carlos was working in your garden? She nodded seriously. We were planting the tomato babies. She said clearly. Carlos was very careful with them because baby plants can die if you're not gentle. What else do you remember? She brightened. Carlos taught me about bugs, and he showed me how his hands were all dirty from the special plant food. He said he couldn't touch anything clean until we wash them. The lawyer asked, did Carlos wash his hands that morning? Oh, yes, she said proudly. We wash them together at the garden faucet with the special soap. Carlos said dirty hands make everything dirty, so we scrubbed until they were super clean. But then Lily added something that changed everything. And Carlos was very sad about his work gloves. The lawyer asked her to explain.

What's the most disgusting experience you've come across while waxing someone? I have one. A girl came into my salon a month before she got married. She had never groomed her pubic hair and claimed to be a virgin. She wanted to be waxed right before her wedding. Completely natural, right? I recommended she get a wax now and another before the big day. Since there was no way of knowing how our prized lady bits would react to the wax, she declined and set an appointment three days before her wedding. Fair enough. When she came back, I was not prepared for the amount of pubic hair she had. It was unusual for a fair skin blonde client to have long, coarse black hair. But whatever, it's my job. So I trim her up, clean her, and prepare to wax her again. She had ungodly amounts of dark hair. Even trimmed, her skin was barely visible. So after inspecting her and not seeing any issues, I begin waxing. I kid you not, she had skin tags and protuberant moles that I did not see. Before starting to get to the point, I pulled a strip from her labia area and pulled off about 20 skin tags. She yelled, the entire salon heard, and then she started bleeding, like gushing blood. We know how to handle bleeding pores, but I had never heard of this. So we're both screaming and crying, and I have to call her an ambulance because She would not stop bleeding. I thought I almost killed her. What I perceived to be skin tags could very well have been human papillomavirus. That being said, her client info form indicated she had no known illness or conditions. Also, I've waxed a few warts before. Sometimes they tear or even bleed, but they don't come off intact the way these did. Yes, obviously the room and equipment was fully sanitized after the incident. I wasn't fired. I didn't get in any trouble. But I did feel guilty. So I voluntarily stood before my state board and told them what happened. It was fine. No repercussions. I never heard from her again, though we did attempt to contact her to check in. Maybe not the grossest story, but it was traumatic. I changed profession soon after. I imagine her wedding night wasn't magical either.

Did you realise your parents were bad at parenting? When I was 10, my mum started sending me to playdates at different friends houses every single day after school. She'd call other parents and say things like, Jake would love to come over and play with Tommy today. Or, Jake's been asking about spending time at your house. At first, I thought I was the most popular kid in school. Every day was like a party at someone else's house. Different toys, different snacks, different video games. I rotate between five or six families throughout the week, never spending more than one evening at home. The other parents were always welcoming. They'd feed me dinner, help with homework, let me stay until bedtime. I started keeping a toothbrush at three different houses because I ended up sleeping over so often. When mom would call saying she got caught up with work or had an unexpected DID meeting, what I didn't realize was that mom was essentially crowd sourcing my care. The other parents thought she was just being social. The pattern became obvious when I started knowing other families routines better than my own. I knew Mrs Brown always made grilled cheese on Wednesdays. I knew the Johnsons had family game night on Fridays. I knew which houses had the good snacks and which parents checked homework carefully. Meanwhile, our own house was always empty. No groceries, no dinner plans, no family activities. Mom would pick me up from someone Else's family dinner and drive me home to microwave leftovers or cereal for dinner. The turning point came when I got sick at school. The nurse called mom, but she was in an important meeting and asked if I could just. Let's go to the Martinez family's house like usual. Mrs. Martinez picked me up, took me to her house, and spent the afternoon taking care of me while her own kids were at soccer practice. That evening, when mom came to collect me, Mrs. Martinez asked to speak with her privately. I was too sick to pay attention, but I heard raised voices from the kitchen. What's the smartest way you've tested your daughter's boyfriend? I pretended I didn't speak English around him for six months and heard everything he said when he thought I couldn't understand. My daughter Emma started dating this guy Kyle last year. Nice looking kid. Always super polite around me and my wife. Maybe too polite. He'd bring flowers every time he came over. Always offered to help with dishes, called me sir non stop. Something felt rehearsed about it. I was born in Brazil, but moved here when I was 10. No accent at all anymore, but my parents taught me to never lose my Portuguese. One night at dinner, Emma mentioned that Kyle was taking Spanish in college. I got this crazy idea. Next time he came over, I pretended I barely spoke English. Just smiled, nodded, and spoke Portuguese with Emma translating that I'd had a stroke that affected my language center. Emma was confused, but played along. When I explained my plan in private, she thought I was being ridiculous, but agreed to help. The first few weeks, Kyle was exactly the same. Super respectful, patient with the language barrier. He even downloaded a translation app. By month, two cracks started showing. When Emma left to use the bathroom, he'd mutter things under his breath. This food is disgusting. How long is this dinner going to take? Once I heard him quietly mock my accent to himself. I pretended not to notice, just smiled and offered more Food. When Emma's birthday came around, Kyle showed up with an expensive bracelet. Later, I overheard him on the phone in our backyard. Yeah, I returned the cheap one.

What's your I didn't start it, but I definitely finished it moment? My high school bully, Jake, tormented me for three years straight. He wasn't your typical bully who just shove you into lockers. No, Jake was calculated. He made sure none of the teachers ever saw anything while systematically destroying my social life. It started sophomore year when I transferred to Westlake High. I didn't know anyone, so I was already nervous. Jake was the star quarterback, student body president, and principal's son. The untouchable golden boy. For reasons I'll never understand, he decided I was his target. At first, it was small stuff. Accidentally knocking my books down, spilling soda on my homework, or spreading rumors that I had weird hobbies. But by junior year, he'd orchestrated my complete isolation. The few friends I'd made suddenly stopped talking to me after Jake told everyone I'd said horrible things about them behind their backs. Ate lunch alone for a year and a half. What kept me going was art. I poured everything into my sculptures, staying late in the art studio almost every day. Miss Porter, our art teacher, recognized my talent and even gave me a key to work weekends. Art became my refuge. In your year, everything changed when the state announced their annual art competition with a 20 thousand dollar college scholarship prize. This was my ticket out. My family couldn't afford college otherwise. Miss Porter encouraged me to enter, saying my metal work sculptures were The best she'd seen from a high school student. For three months, I worked on my masterpiece and intricate wire sculpture showing two hands breaking free from chains. It represented everything I've been through. The detail was incredible. Each link in the chain had tiny engravings of the words that have been used against me. Two weeks before the submission deadline, I walked into the art room and froze. My sculpture lay smashed on the floor, the hundreds of hours of work destroyed beyond repair. On my desk was a yellow sticky note. Oops. Clumsy me, Jay. I felt something break inside me, but not in the way Jake expected. Instead of crying or reporting it, which would have done nothing since his dad ran the school, I smiled and calmly cleaned up the mess. The next day, I started a completely different project. Teacher tried taking my prosthetic leg off in class because she thought I was faking it. I've been wearing a prosthetic leg since I was 9 after bone cancer took my real one. By high school I'd gotten used to explaining it to new teachers, showing my medical documentation, and moving on. Most educators were understanding and supportive, but Mrs. Henderson, our long term substitute for AP Biology, was different from day one. She kept making comments about kids these days faking everything for special treatment and would stare at me whenever I use the elevator or took extra time transitioning between classes. I tried showing her my 5:04 plan and medical records, but she just rolled her eyes and muttered something about convenient paperwork. The breaking point came during a lab practical. I was working at my assigned station when she approached with this smug expression. She whispered that she dealt with attention seeking students before and that my little act wasn't fooling anyone. I explained again that my prosthetic was real, even offering to show her the attachment point, but she just smiled coldly. Prove it, then she said, loudly enough for nearby students to hear, if it's real, you won't mind me checking. Before I could react, she grabbed my prosthetic leg and yanked hard, trying to pull it off like it was some costume piece. The pain was excruciating as the socket twisted against my residual limb. I screamed and fell backward, knocking over lab equipment. As she continued pulling, convinced it would just pop off, the entire class stopped working. Several students started yelling at me. If you don't want to wait for part 2, you can watch the full story on my YouTube channel. We both ordered the same meal we got last time, which was the grilled steak with garlic butter and the seafood paella. It was just as delicious as it was last time. Laura asked if I was nervous about the wedding, and I told her a bit because I hadn't told Todd about my past and hope that it wouldn't make that big of a difference. She said it shouldn't if he really loved me for me. I agreed with her, and we enjoyed the rest of our food and left. The wedding day arrived, and it was time for me to walk down the aisle. The soft music was playing, and I made Laura my maid of honor, just as she had to me. I was greeted with the smiling faces of our family and friends. I felt nervous, but I was happy. As the efficient was about to let us tell our vows, he asked if anyone objected. Voice from behind me said me, and I thought it was a joke at first, so I laughed. Then I turned around to see it was Laura. Then she said with a stern face, I'm serious. The crowd Gasped, and I asked her what she was doing. She said that she knew that I was the one who broke up her and Anthony's wedding. I stood in shock. She said she overheard me and Anthony's conversation in his house months ago, confessing that I recorded our conversation in the restaurant. I asked her what she was talking about, still denying the accusations. I felt my face turning red and sweat was forming under my arms. She said she bugged Anthony's house after the wedding Saturday. I wanted to see if there was another girl I had to worry about. But the only girl I had to worry about was you, my best friend. She screamed. She looked over at Todd, and he looked at me in disgust. She said that not only had she told Todd about my past, but Laura also said she'd been intimate with him for the past year. She said that this was their plan all along and that they would be together now. She ran over to grab Todd, kissed him in front of everyone, and said, if anyone is getting married today, it's gonna be me. The crowd gasped again, and there was a lot of commotion. I ran out crying. I just wanted to be alone at that point. Anthony ran after me to console me. In the dressing room. He hugged me as I cried into his arms. How could she? I said to him. He kept saying that it Was going to be okay

Do you love your mom? When my girlfriend slapped me across the face for the first time, it hurt a lot, but I thought it was just something all girlfriends did, so I just laughed it off and told her not to do it again. As other than that, she was my dream girl. Cook me homemade chicken Alfredo whenever I was sad. She was the first girl to ever get me flowers. And even six months into the relationship, when I paid for our meals together, she's just as grateful as she was on our first date. Plus, it wasn't until eight months into our relationship that a flip had switched, because it was around this time that she found out her dad had been cheating on her mom. It started off small. She'd grab my phone when I got texts just to check who it was. She'd get upset if I talked to my godmother about a book she wrote. You don't need to smile that much when you talk to her, she'd say about the cashier at target. Then came the accusations. If I was five minutes late from work, I was cheating. If I didn't answer her texts immediately, I was with another girl. She'd slap me playfully when other women walked by, but her nails would leave marks when I mentioned it hurt. She'd cry about how I didn't understand what she was going through with her family falling apart. Then came the night where Stella pushed me off the balcony. Luckily, I lived on the first floor of my apartment building. I was just left with two broken ribs and a dislocated shoulder. When I went to the hospital, I told all the nurses that I had just played too much basketball, and the other people in my life were already really suspicious of. So I didn't tell them either. But no matter how much she cried to the doctors or posted about how proud she was of me, there was one woman who wasn't buying into her BS. And that woman was my stepmom. She showed up at my apartment the next day with groceries and her laptop. I'm starting a YouTube channel. She announced home organization and cleaning tips. Very Marie condo meets suburban mom. I thought she lost her mind. She was a tax attorney who could barely operate the TV remote. She sort of gilded me into being her co host using the I pushed you out of me card. And she set up cameras all around my apartment. The bathroom, the kitchen, even my bedroom. At the time, she claimed it was so our audience could get the full experience. The genius part. Stella thought it was pathetic. Some desperate stepmom trying to bond with me through a silly project. She'd mock the videos, call my stepmom cringe, but she never saw her as a threat. Just another stupid woman in my life. During filming, my stepmom would forget To turn off her phone that was recording voice memos for content ideas. She'd schedule emergency reshoots whenever she noticed fresh bruises, making sure to get them on camera. While pretending to film my hands organizing drawer dividers. I had no idea that the whole time, she was just documenting everything. We were three weeks into our channel when Stella lost it. We saw a comment from a woman saying, I had nice hands in our drawer organization video. The camera caught Stella attacking me with a kitchen knife, screaming about how I was just like her father, and how she'd make sure no woman ever looked at me again. When I tried to escape, she cornered me, saying she'd tell everyone I abused her if I ever left. That's when my stepmom walked back in, claiming she'd forgotten her lap.

When did you realize that your best friend never liked you? I was always the dumb, ugly, fat friend, and I wouldn't have it any other way. In high school, my best friend not only got all the guys she wanted, but all the girls, too. She was just that pretty blonde hair that didn't move, smelled like Miss Dior, had a nice butt. So when me and Jasmine would go to the library together and guys would only talk to me to try and get to her, I was happy for her. And when her Snapchat was filled with open snaps from hot guys, while mine just had Team Snapchat and my mom, I was happy for her. Not because she didn't rub it in my face. She did. And not because she didn't see herself as better than me, she absolutely did. But because if I had to pick one of us to be the ugly friend, I would choose me every time. Because even though Jasmine could be a bit of a pick me, deep down I knew she had a soft heart, so she needed the world to be kinder to her more than I did. There was just one thing that made me sad. I knew that she would overly rely on her looks to get her through life. And when high school ended, my theory was already proven right because I graduated with a 4.2 GPA. While the only reason Jasmine didn't flunk out Is because the creepy guidance counselor took a liking to her and convinced all the teachers to grade her tests more kindly. I was actually surprised when she spent all summer working, because with the way the world treated her, making her own money was definitely an optional thing. But when I visited her at her job, I realized her version of working was much, much different from mine. She got hired at the trendy boutique downtown where the manager took one look at her and said she'd be perfect for their brand image. Meanwhile, I spent my summer doing data entry at my dad's friend's accounting firm. Mind numbing work that no one would ever call me perfect for. And the more we talked, the more it became obvious to me that we started to see the world very, very differently. It got to the point where I even had to distance myself from her. I started getting all of my updates about her life from her Instagram instead of our usual Facetimes or texts. In just six months, she had gone from 3,000 followers to 200,000, with her comment sections being filled with thirsty amen. She was getting free clothes from expensive brands, invited to brand events, flown to Coachella. But I knew that most of her new friends were probably using her to make themselves look better, so I always made sure to leave wholesome comments under her posts. I sent her gift packages of stuff I knew she loved on her birthday because I always wanted her to know that someone out there me loved her for who she was, not just for her clout. Honestly, I thought I'd never see her again. Until one day when I was 28. I was a well established lawyer, had my own place, and a boyfriend that loved every inch of me unconditionally. And I guess all the milestones reminded me of when I had graduated from high school. Because one day I found myself reaching out to Jasmine again. I mainly just wanted to see if she had changed and if we could be friends. Cause even though I had met some amazing new people, nothing beats someone from your past. We agreed to meet at the usual ice cream place we'd always spend our pocket money on during high school. When I saw her, it took everything in me to hide the shock I felt because her face was pumped with Botox lip filler, not to mention a pound of makeup. After we got through the awkwardly high pitched how are yous? I cut to the chase. Well, kinda. I casually asked if she was working right now. Um, well, you see, I was, but I just smiled because I had an ace up my sleeve. And that ace was a job offer. I told her I was looking for a secretary and I was willing to pay $65,000 a year with benefits. What do I Look like to you an effing charity case? I stared at her blankly and she threw her plastic filled head back and cackled like it was the funniest thing known to mankind. It had been almost 10 years. There's no way she was still like this. I tried to give her the benefit of the doubt and continued, yeah, so you would have to start ASAP. But, um, she interrupted, don't you know I'm an influencer? She then took out her iPhone and showed me her page. I was gaining a new follower once every four months, and all her DMs were from three years ago. That's when I finally realized Jasmine wasn't some misunderstood pretty girl. She was the washed up, textbook definition of I peaked in high school. I was about to walk away, but she stopped me. Hey, don't be sad. With an A that flat, I would be a lawyer too. I tried to make a B line to my car, but she literally ran in front of me and continued, hey, so when do I get to meet your boyfriend?

Spiked my drink at a party, so I made him terrified of liquids. You know that one guy at every party? The one who thinks he's God's gift to alcohol and women? The guy who says things like, I mix better than I date, and if you can't handle a little fun, go home? Yeah, that guy. For me, that guy had a name. Mason. Mason was the kind of guy who wore sunglasses indoors and took shirtless mirror pics like it was a civic duty. He thought spiking people's drinks was hilarious. Just a little joke, bro. He like slipping something into someone's drink was on par with drawing a mustache on a passed out friend. Spoiler alert, it's not. I found out the hard way. It was during our friend Bailey's New Year's party. Good people, decent music, enough food to soak up the bad decisions. Grab a drink off the kitchen island. Non alcoholic because I was the designated driver. Took a few sips. It tasted a little weird, like if regret had a flavor. I figured maybe the soda was flat. Ten minutes later, the room started spinning like it was trying to detach from earth. I barely made it to the bathroom before my legs went full Jello. My heart was racing, skin crawling, and I was suddenly having a deep, personal conversation with the floor tiles. Bailey found me an hour later, curled up like a shrimp in her tub. She called an ambulance. Thank God. Turns out Mason had decided to spice up the party by adding something to my drink. Something prescription based. Something not meant for conscious humans. He thought it was funny. Dude, you should have seen your face, he said, laughing when I confronted him. Relax, I gave you the light stuff. Ah, yes, just a sprinkle of involuntary coma. How festive. I wanted to punch him, but I'm not stupid. People forget bruises, but they don't forget fear. Especially the kind that seeps in drop by drop. So I made a decision. Mason was going to become terrified of liquids. All of them. The plan took finesse. I couldn't just scream revenge and run at him with a water balloon. This had to feel like karma was slowly dripping down his neck. And it started with coffee. I knew Mason's routine. Every morning, same cafe, same order. Iced triple espresso with oat milk, vanilla, two pumps of ego. So I applied for a job at that cafe. Not because I needed it, but because revenge requires commitment. After three weeks of being the overly eager new guy, I got barista duty. And when Mason walked in, I greeted him with my best you probably don't remember drugging me smile. He didn't recognize me. Perfect. I made his drink. Nothing in it yet, but after handing it to him, I leaned over and said, we've had a few complaints about mold in the oatmeal. Let us

She was worried about online predators or whatever. I told him I just lurk and not embarrass him in front of his friends. For weeks I barely said anything. Just watch these kids play games and talk about school drama. Jake would occasionally type dad, please don't talk when I'd send a simple hi everyone. Then this new game dropped called Stronghold Legends Remastered. It was basically an updated version of this old strategy game from the early 2. Kids were all hyped about it. One night around 10 p. M, this kid named Brandon starts going off in the chat. This game is so easy! These old school players don't know anything about real strategy. My dad tried playing and couldn't even figure out how to build walls properly. Jake types yeah, these older guys just click random stuff and hope it works. Brandon continues bet your dad doesn't even know what a siege engine is. These boomers probably think strategy means buying the biggest army. I'm sitting there in my office drinking coffee watching this unfold. What these kids didn't know was that I was ranked 73rd worldwide. I did in the original Stronghold Legends back in 2003. Oh, no, dad, please don't. From Jake. This is going to be embarrassing. From some other kid Brandon types. Sure, old man. I'll go easy on you. We hop into a 1 v 1 match. voice_to_text: Parents with adopted kids. Why did you choose adoption? The first time I saw my daughter, she was throwing a tantrum in Walmart, and I was just trying to buy milk. She was 4, screaming while her foster mom looked defeated. People stared. The foster mom caught my eye and said, sixth home in eight months. Nobody wants the broken ones. I wasn't planning to adopt. I was 29, divorced, working as a firefighter. But that phrase, nobody wants the broken ones stuck with me for days. A week later, I called the foster agency. Six months after that Walmart tantrum, Lily moved into my home. The social worker warned me, attachment disorder, affected abuse, night terrors. She'll test you. She'll try to prove you'll abandon her, too. The first night, Lily flushed my watch down the toilet. The second night, she poured juice on my laptop. The third night, she screamed for hours that she hated me. I just kept saying, that's okay. I'm still gonna be here tomorrow. By week three, she destroyed half my belongings. My captain pulled me aside. You look like hell. Is this really worth it? That night, I came home to find Lily had cut up all my shirts with Scissors. She watched me, challenging, waiting for the explosion. Instead, I sat down. I'm not sending you back, Lily, I said quietly. No matter what you break. Something shifted in her face. My real dad broke my arm, she whispered, because I spilled Juice. It was the first personal thing she'd ever told me. That night, she had a nightmare and came to my room. Can I stay in here? Just tonight? The real breakthrough came a month later. I came home late from a massive fire. Lily was sitting by the door, clutching her backpack. I thought you weren't coming back, she said, her voice small. I knelt down. I will always come back for you. She studied my face. Promise? Promise. She put down the backpack. Inside were her few precious possessions, ready for another rejection. We were finding our rhythm. When her biological father was released from prison, he filed for custody. The court ordered supervised visits. After the first visit, Lily destroyed her room. After the second, she stopped eating. After the third, she looked at me with panic. Don't make me go back to him. The custody battle lasted 11 months. Every penny went to lawyers. My crew covered for me when I had court. The department passed a hat for legal fees. The turning point came when Lily's father showed up high to a visit. As they were leaving, he grabbed Lily's arm, the same one he'd broken years before. In the emergency hearing, Lily spoke directly to the judge. Seven words that changed everything. I already have a dad. He's right there. The judge terminated the biological father's rights that day. Three months later, we finalized the adoption. Lily wore a firefighter helmet to the courthouse. When the judge asked if she understood what adoption meant, she said, it means even when I break stuff, he fixes it. And he always comes back. Last week was career day, Lily told her class, my dad runs into burning buildings to save people. But first he saved me. I just went to Walmart for milk and came home with a daughter.

Event made you see your mom in a whole new light. I was 12 when my mom lost her job. She'd been the marketing director at her company for nine years. And that night, I found her sitting at our kitchen table with a half empty wine glass stare, staring at nothing. When I asked if she was okay, she just smiled and said, sometimes life gives you a chance to try something new. I didn't understand then how terrified she actually was. Two days later, she started waking up. At 4:00am, I'd hear her moving around downstairs while it was still dark outside. One morning, I crept down to find her hunched over our old sewing machine, surrounded by fabric scraps and design sketches. She jumped when she saw me and quickly covered everything with a sheet. Just a little project, she said, shooing me back to bed. For weeks, she. I barely slept. Dad started complaining about the credit card bills, fabric stores, online craft supplies, shipping materials. They fought in whispers. After they thought I was asleep. I overheard him say, this isn't going to work, Diane. We need real income, not a hobby. She didn't argue back. But the next day, the sewing continued. One afternoon, I came home from school to find our living room transformed into a makeshift photo studio. Mom was photographing small, handmade plush toys against white poster board. When she saw me watching, she looked embarrassed. They're called Pocket Pals. She Explained showing me a tiny stuffed fox with a secret pocket sewn into its back for kids to hide little treasures or notes in. She asked me not to tell my friends about her silly little animals. I didn't understand why until I found her crying in the bathroom a week later. Through tears, she admitted that she'd been rejected by 26 stores already. No one wanted her pocket pals. But instead of giving up, she created a simple website that night. For months, nothing happened. She kept sewing while applying for real jobs during the day. The tension at home was unbearable. Then one morning, she screamed so loud, I thought someone had died. I ran downstairs to find her staring at her laptop in disbelief. Some parenting blogger had featured her pocket pals, calling them the perfect anxiety tool for children. Her website had received over 300 orders overnight. What happened next was chaos. Mom converted our garage into a workshop. She taught me how to sew simple stitches after school, and even dad started helping with packaging on weekends. Orders kept doubling every few weeks. Three months later, a major children's retailer contacted her about a potential partnership. On the night before her big meeting with the retailer, I couldn't sleep and went downstairs for water. I found mom at the kitchen table again, but this time surrounded by her colorful creations. She was sewing a special pocket pal, a purple dragon with silver wings. When she Saw me. She handed it to me. This one's for you, she said. For believing in me when I didn't believe in myself. Last week, five years after she lost her job, I sat in the audience as my mom gave the commencement speech at my high school graduation. The founder of Pocket Pals, now a multi million dollar company that employs over 50 people in our community, told the graduates about resilience and reinvention. The woman who once hid her creations under a sheet now had her products in stores across the country. What no one in that audience knew was how I'd found her business plan. From those early days, her initial goal wasn't to build an empire. It was simply to make enough money to send me to college. The woman I once saw as just mom had transformed herself completely. Not for her own glory, but because she refused to let her circumstances determine my future.

My daughter Lily had just started kindergarten when I got a notification from the class group chat. Hi, everyone, I'm Sarah Miller, and my daughter Tiffany just transferred here today. The chat lit up with a string of welcomes and hellos. Just as I was about to type out my own greeting, a huge block of text appeared. Important notice from Tiffany's mom. Girls in the class, please take note. Starting next week, I'll be posting a picture of what my daughter is wearing each day. Please make sure your child doesn't wear the same thing. Also, I request that everyone please switch to the same brand of laundry detergent we use. My daughter has a very sensitive nose and can't tolerate other scents. Finally, my daughter was a C section baby and is a bit timid, so I ask you to tell your children not to bully her and make sure she's always treated with priority. Wow. I couldn't help but think, this isn't just a new student. This is a royal princess who's slumming it with us commoners. Some of the moms in the chat were quick to push back. Karen's mom are you serious? What my kid wears is none of your business. Why should we have to cater to you? Jessica's mom exactly! And we're supposed to all use your detergent? My son has allergies, too, and we use specific stuff. Yeah, who made your kid the queen of the class? My kid is special too. The Chat quickly devolved into a debate. Usually I just chuckled at the ridiculous things these parents said in the group chat. The class teacher was the administrator, and she'd usually step in to calm things down. I didn't see a problem, so I just muted the chat to get some work done. Then I got a DM. It was from Alyssa, whose daughter Emily was friends with Lily. Hey, Sarah, you got it.

What did you over hear when someone didn't know you understood their language? This happened when I was taking a gap year and backpacking through Europe. I was on this regional train from Milan to Zurich and t b h I was exhausted. I've been travelling for almost three months straight, living off pasta and cheap wine and just wanted to get to my hostel and crash. The train was pretty empty, just me and maybe 10 other people spread throughout the car. I had my headphones in, but wasn't playing anything, just using them as my universal don't talk to me signal. Two guys in their late 20s got on at one of the smaller stops and sat across from me. They were both tall, one with dark hair. Ray and one with this really distinctive scar above his eyebrow. Finn at first I didn't pay much attention, just scrolling through my phone and planning which sites to see in Zurich. But then I heard them start speaking in Italian and I kind of perked up because I've been studying Italian for years. My Nana is from Sicily and she refused to speak English at home when I was growing up, so I'm actually pretty fluent. Ray said something about me being alone and I felt that immediate ick feeling every woman knows, but I kept my face neutral, pretending I was just another clueless American tourist. Then Finn mentioned how I looked tired and probably wouldn't put up Much of a fight. That made my heart start racing, but I forced myself to keep scrolling through my phone like nothing was happening. I noticed Ray taking a photo of me with his phone while pretending to text. That sent chills down my spine. Was he sending my picture to someone? I angled my face away and pulled my hoodie up slightly, trying to seem casual about it. Finn asked Ray if they should do it on the train instead since it was so empty now. Ray shook his head and said the station was safer because they could disappear instantly in different directions. They had a whole system worked out apparently. Ray would create a distraction while Finn grabbed my stuff. Ray mentioned someone who would be waiting in a car near the east exit. Conversation got worse. Ray started describing how they should follow me. When I got off the train, Finn was like what if she screams? And Ray said something about how no one would understand her anyway since they'd be taking her stuff in a less crowded part of the station. I realised they were planning to rob me when I got off the train. I was literally shaking but trying not to show it. My stop was coming up in like 20 minutes and I had no idea what to do. There weren't any other passengers in our car anymore. The ticket checker had already come through. My phone had like 7% battery Left, but I started recording their conversation. And I was carrying almost all my cash and my passport in my backpack. Because the hostel websites warned about lock thefts, I decided to pretend to fall asleep. I leaned against the window and closed my eyes, but kept listening hard to every word they were saying. Ray started going through exactly how they would do it. Follow me through the station to a specific exit he knew was left monitored. Then Finn would grab my backpack while Ray blocked me from running after him. We're so casual about it, like they've done this before. Ray even laughed about some German girl they robbed last week who cried like a baby when they took her camera. I felt sick to my stomach, but kept my breathing steady like I was sleeping. Then the train announcement came on, saying we were 10 minutes from Zurich HB, the main station. I knew I had to do something. I couldn't just walk off the train and let them follow me. I thought about trying to find the conductor, but what if they followed me? What if they just denied everything? I decided to take a huge risk.

When have you seen the real world hit a spoiled brat? I worked as a waiter at this upscale restaurant during college, the kind where entrees cost more than I made in a shift. We had this regular customer, Veronica, who is about 17 and the daughter of some tech CEO. Every Friday night, she'd roll up in a car that cost more than my tuition, with a different group of friends demanding the best table without reservations. The manager always gave in because her father spent thousands there entertaining clients. Veronica had this habit of sending back perfectly good food, claiming it was inedible after taking two bites, changing her order multiple times, and making servers run back and forth for ridiculous requests, like water with exactly three ice cubes, not four. She'd leave her table looking like a tornado hit it. Makeup smeared on our cloth napkins, food deliberately spilled. And the worst part, almost never tipping despite keeping us an hour past closing. One server, Maria, got fired after Veronica complained that she looked at her wrong while serving. Maria was a single mom working three jobs to support her kids. Final straw came during graduation season. Veronica arrived with 10 friends without a reservation during our busiest night of the year. Every table was booked weeks in advance by families celebrating their graduates accomplishments. When the hostess politely explained we couldn't accommodate them, Veronica exploded, screaming that she was more important than these community college losers. And demanding we kick someone out. She whipped out her phone, calling her father and putting him on speaker, expecting him to threaten the restaurant. I was cleaning a nearby table and watch the whole scene unfold. The hostess was nearly in tears as Veronica screamed that she'd get everyone fired. That's when a man at a nearby table stood up. He walked over, calmly, introduced himself as Daniel Morgan, and asked us speak with Veronica's father, who was still on speaker phone. My siblings refused to let me come to their weddings, so I returned the favour. I have four significantly older siblings, all of whom are now married. I wasn't invited to any of their weddings because each one had a child free wedding. I assumed I'd be the exception since I'm their sibling, but no. My oldest sibling was the first to have a child free wedding, and then the others followed suit. When my oldest brother got married, I was 10 years old, so while I was disappointed, I kind of understood why I wasn't invited, but I was still really upset because I loved my brother's wife and I couldn't even be there to witness their wedding. My second brother got married when I was 12, and once again I wasn't invited. At that age, I was a very well behaved kid and I was also his sibling, so I was confused about why I couldn't attend. My sister got married when I was 15. Initially, she didn't plan to have a child free wedding, but the family convinced her by saying how wonderful it would be to have a wedding where children wouldn't cause chaos. So she decided to exclude everyone under 16. When I asked if I could be an exception, given I was her sister and just 15 at the time, she firmly said no. Her reasoning was, if we make an exception for you, what about the other children? It wouldn't be fair. I Got really upset and yelled that it wasn't fair for me to miss all of my siblings weddings. My parents got mad at me for reacting that way and grounded me for six months. The last straw was when my third brother got married. I was 17 by then, so I thought surely I'd be invited to this one. But at that point I had stopped caring. I knew it would be another child free wedding and I somehow wouldn't make the cut. As I expected, I wasn't invited. I didn't even ask or plead. My step cousin, who had just turned 18, was invited, but I wasn't. I wasn't surprised and I didn't care anymore. I just sent a quick congrats text and that was it. My parents were furious and demanded to know why I didn't congratulate them properly. I ignored them and spent the rest of the day with my soon to be husband. Now that I'm getting married, I've decided that none of them will be invited to my wedding since I wasn't allowed to attend theirs when they didn't receive the invitations. My teacher tried taking my prosthetic leg off in class because she thought I was faking it. I've been wearing a prosthetic leg since I was nine after bone cancer took my real one. By high school, I'd gotten used to explaining it to new teachers, showing my medical documentation, and moving on. Most educators were understanding and supportive, but Mrs. Henderson, our long term substitute for A P. Biology, was different from day one. She kept making comments about kids these days faking everything for special treatment, and would stare at me whenever I use the elevator or took extra time transitioning between classes. I tried showing her my 5:04 plan and medical records, but she just rolled her eyes and muttered something about convenient paperwork. The breaking point came during a lab practical. I was working at my assigned station when she approached with this smug expression. She whispered that she'd dealt with attention seeking students before and that my little act wasn't fooling anyone. I explained again that my prosthetic was real, even offering to show her the attachment point, but she just smiled coldly. Prove it, then, she said, loudly enough for nearby students to hear. If it's real, you won't mind me checking. Before I could react, she grabbed my prosthetic leg and yanked hard, trying to pull it off like it was some costume piece. Pain was excruciating as the socket twisted against my residual limb. I screamed and fell backward, knocking over lab Equipment. As she continued pulling, convinced it would just pop off, the entire class stopped working. Several students started yelling.

What's the weirdest past you thought would never catch you? In middle school, I was the meanest girl in our class. Not the popular kind of mean that everyone sees in movies, but the quiet, sneaky kind. I wrote a burn book before Mean Girls made it famous. It was just a pink notebook where I wrote awful things about everyone. Their secrets, their looks, their families. Things I heard in the bathroom or made up when I was bored. My best friend Emma and I would sit at lunch, whispering and laughing while writing in it. We thought we were so cool and smart. No one knew about our book except us. Or so we thought. One day in eighth great, Emma and I had a huge fight over a boy named Tyler. She stopped talking to me, but I kept a burn book. I wrote terrible things about her, too. How her dad lost his job. How she still slept with a nightlight. How her clothes were from Walmart. Stupid kids. Stuff that felt huge back then. When high school started, I made new friends and forgot all about that book. I grew up, realized how awful I'd been, and tried to be better. By college, those mean girl days felt like a different lifetime. I became a teacher, moved to a new city, and built a good life. I never thought about that burn book or those mean days. Ten years later, I was teaching fourth Grade at an elementary school in Chicago. I love my job, my students, and my classroom with its rainbow rug and book corner. I was the teacher I wished I'd had as a kid. Parent teacher conferences came around in October. Over. I sat at my little desk, meeting parents one by one, talking about their kids progress. The door opened for my last meeting of the night, and a woman walked in with a familiar face. My stomach dropped. It was Emma, my old best friend. The one whose secrets I wrote in that burn book. She smiled tightly and sat down. Miss Parker, nice to see you again. I tried to stay calm. Emma, wow. Is Lily your daughter? Lily was one of my quietest students, always reading in the corner. Emma nodded. Yes. Strange coincidence, right? When Lily mentioned her teacher's name, I wasn't sure it was you until I saw the school photo. We talked about Lily's reading skills and math progress. Everything felt normal, but weird. Like we were both pretending. As Emma gathered her papers to leave, I couldn't take it anymore. I'm sorry. I blurted out for everything back then. The things I wrote. I was awful. Emma paused. You know, I found that book after our fight. I took it from your backpack. I read every word. My face burned hot. I'm so sorry. I was terrible person. Yes, you were, she said quietly. I cried for weeks. I waited for her. To yell or say she'd tell the principal about my past. Instead, she pulled out her phone and showed me a picture. It was the burn book. Sitting in a metal trash can, burning. I kept it all these years, not sure what I'd do if I ever saw you again. Then Lily came home, talking about her amazing teacher who makes everyone feel special. Who stands up for the quiet kids, who taught them about bullying. I realized you weren't that girl anymore. She put her phone away. People change. I burned it last night. It's over. The next day, Emma brought cupcakes for the class. As she helped pass them out, she whispered, Lily needs a good teacher. Be that for her. Now. Emma and I get coffee sometimes while Lily reads nearby. We never talk about the Burn Book.

That one time that you had to turn to the dark side. One day, my daughter came back from school and ran into my arms like she was scared. I could feel her shaking, so I took her inside and made some French toast, which was her favorite food. I thought she just had a really bad day and missed being at home, but I couldn't have been more wrong. When she calmed down, she told me, Mommy, something happened today, and I think I'm supposed to tell you about it. An uneasy knot formed itself in my heart when she told me that the school counselor had called her into his office for a special game. He handed my daughter a stuffed unicorn and told her that this new game was very popular with the children, which made my daughter excited and eager to learn. Then the counselor made her point the unicorn between his legs and push on it repeatedly. My daughter told me how he made weird faces at times and then closed his eyes and leaned back. Towards the end, I was so horrified and felt a wave of nausea rush through my body, so I had to go to the bathroom and throw up. What kind of sick person would make a seven year old girl do this kind of thing? Not to mention he worked at a school and it was me who willfully sent my daughter near his vicinity. I kept bouncing between Blaming myself and wanting to burn the entire world. My husband was no longer with us, so it was up to me to stand up for my daughter. I don't know what made me approach the school administration before the police, but that's exactly what I did. And the school administration laughed at me, saying that my daughter was clearly playing a prank. They said they had heard other students make similar jokes about the school counselor and said that parents should teach their kids not to lie. Said, if you ever need someone taken care of, I won't ask for any payment. I typed in that phone number and to my surprise, it actually connected. I told him who I was and he said, I remember you.

But I also had a student named miles who just couldn't sit still. He constantly bugged the girls, always trying to flirt, and it usually ended with him getting slapped or sent to the office. I had sent him down so many times that the front desk basically expected him every day. Eventually, I moved him to the front of the room just so I could keep an eye on him. One day, he asked me if he could sit in the back. He didn't argue or act out. He just asked nicely. For some reason, I said yes. We were in the middle of an assignment, and the entire room was quiet. That's when I heard whispering from the back, looked up, and saw miles showing something to another student. At first glance, it looked exactly like a handgun. I froze for a second. I didn't know if I was seeing it right. Maybe it was a toy or a prop. But I couldn't tell from where I was sitting. And I knew I needed to get a better look without making a scene. I got up to help a student near the back and use that chance to look again. This time I knew for sure it wasn't fake. It was real. I felt sweat drip down my face. My Hands were shaking while I quietly pulled out my phone under the desk and tried to call 9 1 1. But the room was too quiet. I couldn't risk saying anything. I couldn't just leave the class, either. I had to keep everyone safe. And most of all, I needed to get my daughter out of there. I texted the assistant principal in all caps, telling him exactly what I had seen. Then I waited. I kept glancing at my daughter, trying to keep it together, but minutes passed and no response came. I knew I had to do something. I quietly called over one of the students I trusted and handed her a note I had written. It said, ask me to go to the bathroom. Find the assistant principal, show him this text, tell him to check his phone and leave the building right away. She nodded and left without a word. I went back to my desk and acted like nothing was wrong. Five long minutes later, someone knocked on the door. The assistant principal walked in, calm and casual, and started chatting with a couple students near the front. Then he looked at miles. Can I talk to you outside for a minute? I didn't start it, but I definitely finished it. Moment. My high school bully, Jake, tormented me for three years straight. He wasn't your typical bully who just shove you into lockers. No, Jake was calculated. He made sure none of the teachers ever saw anything while systematically destroying my social life. It started sophomore year when I transferred to Westlake High. I didn't know anyone, so I was already nervous. Jake was the star quarterback, student body president and principal's son. The untouchable golden boy. For reasons I'll never understand, he decided I was his target. At first, it was small stuff. Accidentally knocking my books down, spilling soda on my homework, or spreading rumours that I had weird hobbies. But by junior year, he'd orchestrated my complete isolation. The few friends I'd made suddenly stopped talking to me after Jake told everyone I'd said horrible things about them behind their backs. I ate lunch alone for a year and a half. What kept me going was art. I poured everything into my sculptures, staying late in the art studio almost every day. Miss Porter, our art teacher, recognized my talent and even gave me a key to work weekends. Art became my refuge. In your year, everything changed when the state announced their annual art competition with a 20 thousand dollar college scholarship prize. This was my ticket out. My family couldn't afford college otherwise. Miss Porter encouraged me to enter, saying my metal work sculptures were the Best she'd seen from a high school student. For three months, I worked on my masterpiece and intricate wire sculpture showing two hands breaking free from chains. It represented everything I'd been through. The detail was incredible. Each link in the chain had tiny engravings of the words that had been used against me. Two weeks before the submission deadline, I walked into the art room and froze. My sculpture lay smashed on the floor, the hundreds of hours of work destroyed beyond repair. On my desk was a yellow sticky note. Oops. Clumsy me, Jay. I felt something break inside me, but not in the way Jake expected. Instead of crying or reporting it, which would have done nothing since his dad ran the school, I smiled and calmly cleaned up the mess. The next day, I started a completely different project. A technically impressive but intentionally bland wire figure of a tree. Basic, safe, uninspired. What Jake didn't know was that after the destruction, I'd convinced Miss Porter to let me install a small security camera in the art room to prevent further accidents. I also set up a second hidden camera, pointed directly at my supply drawer, where I kept all my original design sketches and concept art. For the next two weeks, I worked on my decoy project during school hours, making sure everyone saw me starting over. But at home in my garage, I was recreating my masterpiece even better than before. Three days before, The deadline. The security footage showed Jake sneaking into the art room at night using a key he must have taken from his dad's office. He went straight to my supply drawer, stealing all my original design sketches for my destroyed sculpture. The day before submissions were due, Jake unveiled his original creation in art class.

Kids didn't know what Christmas was, and it destroyed me. Three years ago, I was working as a social worker when I got assigned to the worst case I'd ever seen. Two siblings, ages 6 and 8, had been locked in a basement for most of their lives by their biological parent. When we found them, they could barely speak, had never seen sunlight, and were so malnourished, they looked like skeletons. The foster system was overwhelmed, and nobody wanted to take two severely traumatized kids. Kids who screamed at every loud noise and couldn't use a bathroom properly. That's when my wife and I made the decision that changed everything. We brought them home, knowing it would be the hardest thing we'd ever do. For months, they wouldn't eat at the dinner table because they thought it was a trap. They hoarded food under their beds, in their closets, even in their shoes. Convinced we'd stop feeding them, they flinched every time we raised our voices, even to call them for dinner. The little girl, Sarah, would only sleep in the closet because open spaces terrified her. Her brother Jake hadn't spoken a single word in the three months they'd been with us. They had nightmares every single night. Sarah would wake up screaming, thinking she was back in that basement. Jake would wet the bed and then try to hide it because he expected to be beaten. Simple things like turning on lights or opening doors would send Them into panic attacks. But slowly, things started to change. Sarah began sleeping in her bed instead of the closet floor. Jake started making eye contact instead of staring at walls. They both began to trust that food would always be there, that we wouldn't hurt them, that this was their real home. Now. We thought we were making real progress. Then December came around, and I started putting up Christmas decoration. That's when I noticed both kids watching me. With your terror in their eyes, backing away from the tree like it was going to attack them. When I asked them what was wrong, Sarah whispered that the bad people used to hurt them more during the light time, because it made them cry louder, and the neighbors couldn't hear them. Over holiday music. I realized they had no idea what Christmas actually was. They'd never gotten presents, never seen Santa, never experienced the joy that every child deserves. Instead, their violators had used the season as an excuse for horrible things, telling them that nobody cared about them, while other kids got gifts, that Santa only visited good children, and they were too broken and worthless. When I gently explained what Christmas really meant, family, love, presents, and a magical man who brings joy to children, Sarah looked at me like I was telling her fairy tales. Just stared at the floor, refusing to believe anything good could happen to him. They couldn't comprehend that a holiday could Bring happiness instead of pain. On Christmas Eve, I stayed up all night setting up the most magical Christmas morning I could imagine. I left cookies half eaten, milk glasses empty, and muddy boot prints leading from the fireplace to the tree. I wrapped dozens of presents and filled their stockings until they overflowed. I even left a note from Santa saying how proud he was of them. But what happened Christmas morning broke me in the best possible way.

Poor people who have dated rich people. What did you learn? I dated a tech CEO's daughter in college, never knowing who her family was until three months in. We met at a campus coffee shop where she worked part time. I assumed she needed the money like me, another struggling student trying to make ends meet. She wore thrift store clothes, drove a beat up Honda with dents in the side, and lived in a normal dorm room with a roommate. Her name was Emily, and I fell for her laugh. First she'd snort a little when something was really funny, then get embarrassed about it. We started hanging out after her shifts. Sometimes we'd split a sandwich because neither of us claimed to have enough money for a full meal. I was working two jobs between classes, and she'd always insist on studying together so I wouldn't have to choose between grades and sleep. One weekend, about three months in, she invited me to her family home for spring break. Said it would save us both money. Instead of staying in the dorms, I packed my one decent shirt and jeans without holes. The drive took two hours. As we left the city, the houses got bigger. Then we turned onto a private road and pulled up to a gated entrance with actual security guards who knew her by name. My stomach dropped as we drove another half mile up a winding driveway to what I can only Describe as a modern castle, glass and steel, perched on a Hillside overlooking the ocean. What the hell? Emily? Was all I could manage to say. She bit her lip, looking more nervous than I'd ever seen her. My dad started. Made a software when I was a kid. Kind of took off. Took off was an understatement. Why work at a coffee shop when your dad's worth billions? I asked while staring at the indoor pool, visible through the floor to ceiling windows. He looked away and said, people treat me differently when they know either they want something or they assume I'm a spoiled brat. I just wanted someone to like me for me. That first night was surreal. Their chef? Yes, they had a personal chef. Prepared a dinner that probably cost more than my monthly food budget. Emily's father, whose face I'd seen on magazine covers, at the head of the table, studying me during dessert. He finally spoke directly to me. So what's your five year plan? The question felt like a trap. I could have lied, could have made up some impressive sounding career trajectory. Instead, I told him honestly that I was studying engineering, had $80,000 in student loans. I hope to get a job that would let me pay them off before I was 40. The table went completely silent. Emily's mother paused with her wine glass halfway through her lips. Then her dad laughed. A genuine, unexpected laugh. Finally, someone tell
